{{Use British English|date=December 2021}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2023}}
{{Transgender sidebar|rights}}
{{Feminism sidebar|expanded=other variants}}

'''Gender-critical feminism''', also known as '''trans-exclusionary radical feminism''' or '''TERFism''',<ref name="Thurlow" /><ref name="Williams" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rogers |first1=Baker A. |date=2023 |title=TERFs aren't feminists: lesbians stand against trans exclusion |journal=[[Journal of Lesbian Studies]] |volume=28 |issue=1 |pages=24–43 |doi=10.1080/10894160.2023.2252286 |pmid=37679960 |s2cid=261608725 |quote=many lesbians despise TERF ideology}}</ref><ref name=Bassi/> is an ideology or movement that opposes what it refers to as "[[gender ideology]]",<ref name="Pearce">{{Cite journal |last1=Pearce |first1=Ruth |author-link=Ruth Pearce (sociologist) |last2=Erikainen |first2=Sonja |last3=Vincent |first3=Ben |year=2020 |title=TERF wars: An introduction |url=https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/0038026120934713 |url-status=live |journal=[[The Sociological Review]] |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=677–698 |doi=10.1177/0038026120934713 |s2cid=221097475 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211120190817/https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/0038026120934713 |archive-date=20 November 2021 |access-date=7 December 2021 |hdl-access=free |hdl=2164/18988}}</ref> the concept of [[gender identity]] and [[transgender rights]], especially [[gender self-identification]]. Gender-critical feminists believe that [[sex]] is biological and immutable,<ref>{{Cite web |last=UK Parliament |title=Employment Tribunal rulings on gender-critical beliefs in the workplace |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/employment-tribunal-rulings-on-gender-critical-beliefs-in-the-workplace/ |access-date=22 October 2023 |website=House of Commons Library |archive-date=11 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240511054729/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/employment-tribunal-rulings-on-gender-critical-beliefs-in-the-workplace/ |url-status=live }}</ref> while believing gender, including both gender identity and [[gender roles]], to be inherently oppressive. They reject the concept of [[transgender]] identities.<ref name=":0">{{Citation |last1=Sullivan |first1=Alice |title=Introduction |date=10 July 2023 |url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9781003286608/chapters/10.4324/9781003286608-1 |work=Sex and Gender |pages=1–15 |access-date=20 October 2023 |edition=1 |place=London |publisher=Routledge |language=en |doi=10.4324/9781003286608-1 |isbn=978-1-003-28660-8 |last2=Todd |first2=Selina}}</ref>

Originating as a [[fringe movement|fringe]] movement within [[radical feminism]] mainly in the [[United States]],<ref name="Bassi" /><ref name=Thomsen/><ref name=BD/> trans-exclusionary radical feminism has achieved prominence in the [[United Kingdom]]<ref name="HinesSocRev" /> and [[South Korea]],<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite journal |last=Lee |first=Hyun-Jae |date=December 2020 |title=A Critical Study of Identity Politics Based on the Category 'Biological Woman' in the Digital Era: How Young Korean Women Became Transgender Exclusive Radical Feminists |journal=Journal of Asian Sociology |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=425–448 |doi=10.21588/dns.2020.49.4.003 |jstor=26979894 |doi-access=free }}</ref> where it has been at the centre of high-profile controversies. It has been linked to promotion of [[disinformation]]<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal |last=Billard |first=Thomas J |date=2023-04-03 |title="Gender-Critical" Discourse as Disinformation: Unpacking TERF Strategies of Political Communication |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07491409.2023.2193545 |journal=Women's Studies in Communication |language=en |volume=46 |issue=2 |pages=235–243 |doi=10.1080/07491409.2023.2193545 |issn=0749-1409 |s2cid=258464300 |access-date=23 October 2023 |archive-date=2 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702134717/https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07491409.2023.2193545 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book |last1=Willem |first1=Cilia |last2=Platero |first2=R. Lucas |last3=Tortajada |first3=Iolanda |year=2022 |chapter=Trans-exclusionary Discourses on Social Media in Spain |title=Identities and Intimacies on Social Media |location=Abingdon, UK |publisher=Routledge |pages=185–200 |doi=10.4324/9781003250982-15 |doi-access=free |isbn=978-1-003-25098-2 |oclc=1334107848}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite journal |last=Tudor |first=Alyosxa |date=May 2023 |title=The anti-feminism of anti-trans feminism |journal=European Journal of Women's Studies |language=en |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=290–302 |doi=10.1177/13505068231164217 |issn=1350-5068 |doi-access=free}}</ref> and to the [[anti-gender movement]].<ref name="Council of Europe 2021" /> Anti-gender rhetoric has seen increasing circulation in gender-critical feminist discourse since 2016, including use of the term "[[gender ideology]]".<ref name="Pearce" /> In several countries, gender-critical feminist groups have formed alliances with right-wing, [[far-right]], and [[anti-feminist]] organisations.<ref name="Butler idea of 'gender' backlash">{{cite news |last1=Butler |first1=Judith |title=Why is the idea of 'gender' provoking backlash the world over? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/commentisfree/2021/oct/23/judith-butler-gender-ideology-backlash |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211117074438/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/commentisfree/2021/oct/23/judith-butler-gender-ideology-backlash |archive-date=17 November 2021 |access-date=17 November 2021 |work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name="CTV hate rise Canada">{{cite news |title='Rights aren't a competition': Anti-trans hate is on the rise in Canada, activists and advocates say |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/rights-aren-t-a-competition-anti-trans-hate-is-on-the-rise-in-canada-activists-and-advocates-say-1.5530155 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211129071026/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/rights-aren-t-a-competition-anti-trans-hate-is-on-the-rise-in-canada-activists-and-advocates-say-1.5530155 |archive-date=29 November 2021 |access-date=29 November 2021 |work=CTV News}}</ref><ref name="Alm & Engebretsen 2020">{{cite journal |last1=Alm |first1=Erika |last2=Engebretsen |first2=Elisabeth L. |date=15 June 2020 |title=Gender Self-identification |journal=Lambda Nordica |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=48–56 |doi=10.34041/ln.v25.613 |s2cid=225712334 |doi-access=free |hdl-access=free |hdl=11250/3048285}}</ref><ref name="Studnik">{{cite news |last1=Studnik |first1=Joane |date=24 January 2023 |title=Was bedeutet TERF? Wie linke Transfeindlichkeit Rechtsextreme stärkt |trans-title=What does TERF mean? How left-wing transphobia strengthens the far right |url=https://www.freitag.de/autoren/joane-studnik/was-bedeutet-terf-wie-linke-transfeindlichkeit-rechtsextreme-staerkt |work=[[Der Freitag]]}}</ref>

Gender-critical feminism has been described as [[transphobia|transphobic]] by feminist and scholarly critics,<ref name="Thurlow" /><ref name="Bassi" /> and is opposed by many feminist, [[LGBT rights organization|LGBT rights]], and [[human rights organization]]s.<ref name="Canada 110" /><ref name="Toutes des femmes" /> The [[Council of Europe]] has condemned gender-critical ideology, among other ideologies, and linked it to "virulent attacks on the rights of [[Intersex and LGBT|LGBTI]] people" in [[Hungary]], [[Poland]], [[Russia]], [[Turkey]], the United Kingdom, and other countries.<ref name="Resolution2417" /> [[UN Women]] has described the gender-critical movement, among other movements, as extreme [[anti-rights movements]] that employ [[hate propaganda]] and disinformation.<ref name="unwomen" /><ref name="thetimesantirights" />

== Terminology ==

=== Trans-exclusionary radical feminism ===
{{main|TERF (acronym)}}

Trans-inclusive [[cisgender]] radical feminist [[blogger]] Viv Smythe has been credited with popularizing the term "trans-exclusionary radical feminism" in 2008 as an online [[shorthand]].<ref name="Smythe 2018">{{cite news |last1=Smythe |first1=Viv |title=I'm credited with having coined the word 'Terf'. Here's how it happened |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 November 2018 |access-date=13 April 2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/nov/29/im-credited-with-having-coined-the-acronym-terf-heres-how-it-happened |quote=Due to a short series of blogposts from 2008, I have retrospectively been credited as the coiner of the acronym "Terf" (Trans Exclusionary Radical Feminists) ... a shorthand to describe one cohort of feminists who self-identify as radical and are unwilling to recognise trans women as sisters, unlike those of us who do. |archive-date=25 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125115202/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/nov/29/im-credited-with-having-coined-the-acronym-terf-heres-how-it-happened |url-status=live }}</ref> It was used to describe a minority of [[Feminism|feminists]]<ref name="Stryker TSQ">{{cite journal |last1=Stryker |first1=Susan |authorlink1=Susan Stryker |last2=Bettcher |first2=Talia M. |title=Introduction |journal=[[Transgender Studies Quarterly]] |date=1 May 2016 |volume=3 |issue=1–2 |pages=5–14 |doi=10.1215/23289252-3334127 |doi-access=free }}</ref> who espouse sentiments that other feminists consider [[transphobia|transphobic]],<ref name="Dastagir 2017">{{cite news |last1=Dastagir |first1=Alia |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/03/16/feminism-glossary-lexicon-language/99120600/ |title=A feminist glossary because we didn't all major in gender studies |work=[[USA Today]] |date=16 March 2017 |access-date=24 April 2019 |quote=TERF: The acronym for 'trans exclusionary radical feminists,' referring to feminists who are transphobic. |archive-date=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720073940/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/03/16/feminism-glossary-lexicon-language/99120600/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2018/12/famous-lesbian-site-taken-anti-trans-feminists-now-lesbian-media-standing/|title=Famous lesbian site taken over by anti-trans 'feminists'. Now lesbian media is standing up.|last=Bollinger|first=Alex|date=19 December 2018|website=www.lgbtqnation.com|access-date=5 June 2019|archive-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605233013/https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2018/12/famous-lesbian-site-taken-anti-trans-feminists-now-lesbian-media-standing/|url-status=live}}</ref> including the rejection of the predominant view in feminist organizations that trans women are women,<ref name="Burns 2019">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Katelyn |date=5 September 2019 |title=The rise of anti-trans "radical" feminists, explained |url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2019/9/5/20840101/terfs-radical-feminists-gender-critical |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200811100302/https://www.vox.com/identities/2019/9/5/20840101/terfs-radical-feminists-gender-critical |archive-date=11 August 2020 |access-date=29 August 2022 |website=Vox |quote="I don't think American women are buying it", she said, pointing out that nearly every major US feminist advocacy group is vocally pro-trans rights and inclusion.}}</ref> opposition to [[transgender rights]],<ref name="Burns 2019" /> and the exclusion of trans women in women's spaces and organizations.<ref name="O'Connell 2019">{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/health-family/transgender-for-beginners-trans-terf-cis-and-safe-spaces-1.3769653 |title=Transgender for beginners: Trans, terf, cis and safe spaces |last1=O'Connell |first1=Jennifer |newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en |date=26 January 2019 |access-date=24 April 2019 |archive-date=26 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126223339/https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/health-family/transgender-for-beginners-trans-terf-cis-and-safe-spaces-1.3769653 |url-status=live }}</ref> Smythe has also been credited with having coined the acronym "TERF", due to a blog post she wrote reacting to the [[Michigan Womyn's Music Festival]]'s [[Michigan Womyn's Music Festival#"Womyn-born womyn" policy|policy]] of denying admittance to trans women. Though it was created as a deliberately neutral descriptor, "TERF" is now typically considered [[derogatory]].<ref name="TerfOED">{{Cite OED|term=TERF|id=98002894|access-date=14 July 2022|date=June 2022}}</ref>

===Gender-critical feminism===
Claire Thurlow said that since the 2010s, there has been a shift in language from "TERF" to "gender critical feminism", which she described as a [[dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]] for anti-trans politics.<ref name=Thurlow/> Researcher Aleardo Zanghellini argues that "gender-critical feminism advocates reserving women's spaces for [[Cisgender|cis]] women".<ref name="Zanghellini 14">{{Cite journal |last=Zanghellini |first=Aleardo |date=April–June 2020 |title=Philosophical Problems With the Gender-Critical Feminist Argument Against Trans Inclusion |journal=SAGE Open |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=14 |doi=10.1177/2158244020927029 |doi-access=free }}</ref> [[Mauro Cabral Grinspan]], Ilana Eloit, [[David Paternotte]] and [[Mieke Verloo]] describe "gender-critical feminism" as a "self-definition by some individuals and groups labelled TERFs" and argue that the term is problematic because it serves to rebrand anti-trans activism.<ref name=Grinspan>{{cite journal |last1=Grinspan |first1=Mauro Cabral |last2=Eloit |first2=Ilana |last3=Paternotte |first3=David|author-link3=David Paternotte |last4=Verloo |first4=Mieke |title=Exploring TERFnesses |journal=Journal of Diversity and Gender Studies |date=2023 |volume=10 |issue=2 |doi=10.21825/digest.90008|doi-access=free }}</ref>

== Views ==
{{further|Feminist views on transgender topics}}

=== Sex and gender ===
{{See also|Sex–gender distinction}}
Gender-critical feminists equate "women" with what they consider to be a "female sex class", and view historical and contemporary oppression of women as being rooted in their being female, while "gender" is a system of social norms which functions to oppress women on the basis of their sex.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Woman as Resource: A Reply to Catharine MacKinnon - The Philosophers' Magazine |url=https://www.philosophersmag.com/essays/318-woman-as-resource-a-reply-to-catharine-mackinnon |access-date=21 October 2023 |website=www.philosophersmag.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kodsi |first1=Daniel |title=Who is feminism for? |date=3 July 2022 |url=https://thecritic.co.uk/who-is-feminism-for/ |access-date=14 August 2023 |archive-date=14 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230814084232/https://thecritic.co.uk/who-is-feminism-for/ |url-status=live }}</ref> They believe sex is biological and cannot be changed,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brione |first1=Patrick |title=Employment Tribunal rulings on gender-critical beliefs in the workplace |url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/employment-tribunal-rulings-on-gender-critical-beliefs-in-the-workplace |access-date=14 August 2023 |archive-date=10 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230710111234/https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/employment-tribunal-rulings-on-gender-critical-beliefs-in-the-workplace/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and that equity legislation protecting against discrimination based on sex should be interpreted as solely referring to biological sex.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elgot |first1=Jessica |title=Kemi Badenoch could rewrite law to allow trans exclusion from single-sex spaces |url=https://amp.theguardian.com/society/2023/apr/04/kemi-badenoch-could-rewrite-law-to-allow-trans-exclusion-from-single-sex-spaces |access-date=14 August 2023 |work=The Guardian |date=4 April 2023}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=Source only mentions gender-critical views in passing and doesn't really describe this as a core attribute of them, just as a position some groups took in one legal dispute.|date=October 2024}} Furthermore, gender critics emphasise the view that sex is binary,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cowan |first1=Sharon |last2=Morris |first2=Sean |title=Should 'Gender Critical' Views about Trans People Be Protected as Philosophical Beliefs in the Workplace? Lessons for the Future from Forstater, Mackereth and Higgs |journal=Industrial Law Journal |date=2022 |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=1–37 |doi=10.1093/indlaw/dwac002 |url=https://academic.oup.com/ilj/article/51/1/1/6536993|doi-access=free |hdl=20.500.11820/283d153e-d5df-4e5c-89c5-04da82e6795d |hdl-access=free }}</ref> as opposed to a continuous spectrum, and that the two sexes have an objective, material basis as opposed to being socially constructed.<ref name="stock_material_girls_ch2">{{cite book |last1=Stock |first1=Kathleen |title=Material Girls: Why Reality Matters for Feminism |date=2021 |publisher=Fleet |isbn=9780349726595 |pages=44–75 |chapter=Chapter 2: What is sex?}}</ref>

Gender-critical feminists promote the idea that sex is important.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawford-Smith |first1=Holly |title=Gender-Critical Feminism |date=2022 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780198863885}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sex Matters to intervene in Equality Act case at Inner House |url=https://www.scottishlegal.com/articles/sex-matters-to-intervene-in-case-on-meaning-of-sex-in-equality-act |access-date=21 October 2023 |work=Scottish Legal News |date=3 October 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Searles |first1=Michael |title=Government to tell GMC 'women are women' and 'biological sex matters' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/10/17/government-tell-gmc-women-are-women-biological-sex-matters/ |access-date=21 October 2023 |work=The Telegraph |date=17 October 2023}}</ref> In ''[[Material Girls: Why Reality Matters for Feminism|Material Girls]]'', [[Kathleen Stock]] discusses four areas in which she expresses the view that sex-associated differences are important, regardless of gender: [[Sex differences in medicine|medicine]], sport, [[sexual orientation]], and the social effects of heterosexuality (such as [[gender pay gap]]s and [[sexual assault]]).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stock |first1=Kathleen |title=Material Girls: Why Reality Matters for Feminism |date=2021 |publisher=Fleet |isbn=9780349726595 |pages=76–108 |chapter=Chapter 3: Why does sex matter?}}</ref> [[Holly Lawford-Smith]] states: "Gender critical feminism is ''not'' 'about' trans. It is ''about'' sex."<ref name="hls_what_is_gcf">{{cite web |last1=Lawford-Smith |first1=Holly |title=What Is Gender Critical Feminism (and why is everyone so mad about it)? |date=29 March 2021 |url=https://hollylawford-smith.org/what-is-gender-critical-feminism-and-why-is-everyone-so-mad-about-it/ |access-date=21 October 2023}}</ref> Lawford-Smith said of gender-critical feminism: "It is about being critical of gender, and this has implications for a wide range of feminist issues, not just gender identity." Writing of her view of a "gender-critical feminist utopia", she said: "While there will still be the same ''people'' who think of themselves as 'transmen', 'transwomen' or 'non-binary' today, they will not use those labels, because 'feminine' will be a way that males can be, 'masculine' will be a way that women can be, and 'androgynous' will be a way that anyone can be."<ref name="H L Smith 2022">{{cite book |last1=Lawford-Smith |first1=Holly |title=Gender-Critical Feminism |date=2022 |publisher=OUP |isbn=978-0-19-886388-5 |pages=13, 166}}</ref>

In gender-critical discourse, the terms ''man'' and ''woman'' are used as sex-terms, assigned no more meaning than ''adult human male'' and ''adult human female'' respectively, in contrast to feminist theorists who argue these terms embody a social category distinct from matters of biology (usually referred to as ''gender''), with ''masculinity'' and ''femininity'' representing normative characteristics thereof.<ref>{{cite web |title=Feminist Perspectives on Sex and Gender |url=https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/feminism-gender/#SexDis |website=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy |access-date=15 August 2023 |archive-date=1 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220601002408/https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/feminism-gender/#SexDis |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Byrne |first1=Alex |title=Are women adult human females? |journal=Philosophical Studies |date=January 2020 |volume=177 |issue=12 |page=22 |doi=10.1007/s11098-019-01408-8 |hdl=1721.1/128358 |s2cid=254943344 |url=https://dspace.mit.edu/bitstream/handle/1721.1/128358/11098_2019_1408_ReferencePDF.pdf |access-date=15 August 2023 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042322/https://dspace.mit.edu/bitstream/handle/1721.1/128358/11098_2019_1408_ReferencePDF.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The phrase ''adult human female'' has become a [[slogan]] in gender-critical politics, and has been described as transphobic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Woman billboard removed after transphobia row |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-45650462 |access-date=15 August 2023 |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2018 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042326/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45650462 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== "Sex-based rights" ===
[[File:TERF sticker.jpg|thumb|A sticker promoting gender-critical feminism]]
Gender critical feminists advocate what they call "sex-based rights", arguing that "women's human rights are based upon sex" and that "these rights are being eroded by the promotion of 'gender identity'".<ref name="HinesSocRev">{{cite journal |last1=Hines |first1=Sally |title=Sex wars and (trans) gender panics: Identity and body politics in contemporary UK feminism |journal=[[The Sociological Review]] |date=2020 |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=699–717 |doi=10.1177/0038026120934684 |s2cid=221097483 |url=https://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/163972/8/0038026120934684.pdf |access-date=16 June 2023 |archive-date=14 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211214191345/https://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/163972/8/0038026120934684.pdf |url-status=live |doi-access=free}}</ref>

Human rights scholar Sandra Duffy described the concept of "sex-based rights" as "a fiction with the pretense of legality", noting that the word "sex" in [[international human rights law]] does not share the implications of the word "sex" in gender-critical discourse and is widely agreed to also refer to [[gender]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duffy |first1=Sandra |title=An International Human Rights Law Analysis of the WHRC Declaration |date=26 October 2021 |url=https://sandraduffy.wordpress.com/2021/10/26/an-international-human-rights-law-analysis-of-the-whrc-declaration/ |access-date=4 December 2021 |archive-date=16 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220616105029/https://sandraduffy.wordpress.com/2021/10/26/an-international-human-rights-law-analysis-of-the-whrc-declaration/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Catharine A. MacKinnon]] noted that "the recognition [that discrimination against trans people is discrimination on the basis of sex, that is gender, the social meaning of sex] does not, contrary to allegations of anti-trans self-identified feminists, endanger women or feminism", they expand by saying "women do not have 'sex-based rights' in the affirmative sense some in this group seem to think".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=MacKinnon |first1=Catharine A. |author-link=Catharine A. MacKinnon |date=2023 |title=A Feminist Defense of Transgender Sex Equality Rights |url=https://openyls.law.yale.edu/bitstream/handle/20.500.13051/18252/88.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |journal=[[Yale Journal of Law and Feminism]] |volume=34}}</ref>

=== Socialisation and gender nonconformity ===
Gender critical feminists generally see gender as a system in which women are oppressed for reasons intrinsically related to their sex, and emphasize male violence against women, particularly involving institutions such as the [[sex industry]], as central to women's oppression.<ref name="McKay 2015">{{cite journal |last1=Mackay |first1=Finn |title=Radical Feminism |journal=Theory, Culture & Society |date=December 2015 |volume=32 |issue=7–8 |pages=332–336 |doi=10.1177/0263276415616682 |s2cid=220719287 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bettcher |first1=Talia Mae |editor1-last=Disch |editor1-first=Lisa |editor2-last=Hawkesworth |editor2-first=Mary |title=The Oxford Handbook of Feminist Theory |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=9780199328581 |pages=407–427 |chapter=Intersexuality, transgender and transsexuality|year=2016 }}</ref> Holders of such views often contend that trans women cannot fully be women because they were assigned male at birth and have experienced some degree of [[male privilege]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schmidt |first1=Samantha |title=Women's issues are different from trans women's issues, feminist author says, sparking criticism |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/13/womens-issues-are-different-from-trans-womens-issues-feminist-author-says-sparking-criticism/?noredirect=on |access-date=11 October 2018 |agency=Washington Post |date=13 March 2017 |archive-date=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017045301/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/03/13/womens-issues-are-different-from-trans-womens-issues-feminist-author-says-sparking-criticism/?noredirect=on |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Germaine Greer]] has said that it "wasn't fair" that "a man who has lived for 40 years as a man and had children with a woman and enjoyed the services—the unpaid services of a wife, which most women will never know…then decides that the whole time he's been a woman".<ref name="timegreer">{{Cite news |url=https://time.com/4290409/germaine-greer-transgender-women/ |work=Time Magazine |title=Germaine Greer Defends Her Controversial Views on Transgender Women}}</ref>

These ideas have been met with criticism from believers in other branches of feminism. Sociologist Patricia Elliot argues that the view that one's socialization as a girl or woman defines "women's experience" assumes that cis women's experiences are homogeneous and discounts the possibility that trans and cis women may share the experience of being disparaged for their perceived femininity.<ref name="Elliot_2004">{{cite journal |last1=Elliot |first1=Patricia |title=Who Gets to Be a Woman?: Feminist Politics and the Question of Trans-inclusion |journal=Atlantis: Critical Studies in Gender, Culture & Social Justice |date=2004 |volume=29 |issue=1 |page=16 |url=http://journals.msvu.ca/index.php/atlantis/article/view/1166 |access-date=12 October 2018 |quote=The first assumption is that one's socialization as a girl or woman defines "women's experience" as something shared. But this assumption downplays differences among women, as if the sociological norms one identifies as part of a patriarchal gender order are evenly applied to all in one cookie-cutter model, or as if girls and women have the same relationships to those norms. It also fails to ask about possible similarities of experience between trans and non-trans women (both of whom may have been disparaged for their femininity). |archive-date=12 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214554/http://journals.msvu.ca/index.php/atlantis/article/view/1166 |url-status=live }}</ref> Others argue that expectations of one's assigned sex are something enforced upon them, beginning at early socialization, and transgender youth, especially gender-nonconforming children, often experience different, worse treatment involving reprisals for their deviation therefrom.<ref name="Dietert_Dentice">{{cite journal |last1=Dietert |first1=Michelle |last2=Dentice |first2=Dianne |title=Growing up trans: Socialization and the gender binary |journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies |date=2012 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=24–42 |quote=When individuals deviate from gender binary arrangements by expressing gender norms and roles not associated with their biological assignment at birth, authorities submit control by utilizing gender binary discourse beginning in early socialization and lasting throughout the individual's life. During early socialization, we suggest that transgender individuals must negotiate their family and peer relationships relative to established, norm-driven gender binary discourse which oftentimes result in anxiety, fear of appraisals for not conforming to gender norms, and differential treatment from both family members and peers.|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2013.746053 |s2cid=143015502 }}</ref>

Transfeminist [[Julia Serano]] has referred to implying that trans women may experience some degree of male privilege pre-transition as "denying [them] [[the closet]]", and has compared it to saying that a cisgender gay person experienced straight privilege before coming out. She has also compared it to if a cisgender girl was raised as a boy against her will, and how the two scenarios tend to be viewed differently by a cisgender audience, despite being ostensibly similar experiences from a transfeminine perspective.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://juliaserano.medium.com/why-are-amab-trans-people-denied-the-closet-7fd5c740ce30 |title=Why are AMAB trans people denied the closet? |last1=Serano |first1=Julia |date=2 March 2022 |access-date=16 January 2023 |archive-date=16 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230116234350/https://juliaserano.medium.com/why-are-amab-trans-people-denied-the-closet-7fd5c740ce30 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Gender transition ===

In ''[[The Transsexual Empire]]'' (1979), feminist Janice Raymond denounces the act of transition as "rape", by virtue of "reducing the real female form to an artifact, appropriating this body for themselves".<ref>Raymond, Janice. (1994). ''The Transsexual Empire'', p. 104</ref> [[Helen Joyce]] has described people who undergo transition, whether happier for it or not, as "a huge problem to a sane world".<ref>{{Cite news |work=PinkNews |url=https://www.thepinknews.com/2022/06/03/helen-joyce-transgender-lgbtq/ |title='Gender critical' author Helen Joyce says she wants to 'reduce' number of trans people: 'Chilling'}}</ref>

In her own book ''[[Gyn/Ecology]]'' (1979), originally published one year earlier, [[Mary Daly]], who had served as Raymond's thesis supervisor,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Feminist theologian Mary Daly dies|url=https://www.ebar.com/news///240420|access-date=3 July 2020|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|archive-date=8 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308171932/https://www.ebar.com/news///240420|url-status=live}}</ref> insisted that as sex reassignment surgery could not reproduce female chromosomes, the clitoris, the ability to give birth, the ability to menstruate, or a female life history, it could "not produce women".<ref name="Daly">{{cite book |last=Daly |first=Mary |author-link=Mary Daly |date=1981 |orig-date=1978 |title=Gyn/Ecology: The Metaethics of Radical Feminism |location=London |publisher=The Women's Press}}</ref>{{rp|67–68}} [[Sheila Jeffreys]] and [[Germaine Greer]] have made similar remarks.<ref name="BINDEL2">{{cite news | last= Bindel | first= Julie | author-link= Julie Bindel | title= The ugly side of beauty | work= [[The Guardian]] | date= 2 July 2005 | url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jul/02/gender.politicsphilosophyandsociety | access-date= 16 June 2023 | archive-date= 25 February 2021 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210225140358/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jul/02/gender.politicsphilosophyandsociety | url-status= live }}</ref> Daly presented gender transition as the result of a grotesque patriarchal urge to violate natural boundaries and imitate motherhood, assimilating it to a broader concept of "male motherhood" that also included the Catholic priesthood, and claimed that it represented a male technological attempt to replace women altogether.<ref name="Daly" />{{rp|71–72}} She also compared the idea that a trans woman could be a woman despite lacking a clitoris to the ideology behind "African [[female genital mutilation]]".<ref name="Daly" />{{rp|167}}

In a response to remarks by [[Elizabeth Grosz]], philosopher [[Eva Simone Hayward|Eva Hayward]] characterized this type of view as telling trans people who have had sex reassignment surgery: "Don't exist."<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hayward |first1=Eva S. |title=Don't Exist |journal=[[Transgender Studies Quarterly]] |date=2017 |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=191–194|doi=10.1215/23289252-3814985 }}</ref>

===Intersex conditions===
Radical feminist [[Germaine Greer]] called women with XY [[Androgen insensitivity syndrome|AIS]] "men" and "incomplete males" in her 1999 book ''The Whole Woman''. [[Iain Morland]] responded that "in trying to criticize the social construction of femaleness and intersex, Greer disenfranchised precisely those people who live at the intersection of the two categories".<ref>{{cite web|title=''Progress and Politics in the intersex rights movement, Feminist theory in action''|url=http://www.aisia.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Dreger__Herndon_2009.pdf|author1=Alice D. Dreger|author2=April M. Herndon|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=21 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230621132342/http://www.aisia.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Dreger__Herndon_2009.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232519105|title=Intersex Activism, Feminism and Psychology: Opening a Dialogue on Theory, Research and Clinical Practice &#124; Request PDF}}</ref> Greer admitted in 2016 that defining men and women solely using chromosomes was wrong.<ref name="timegreer" /> Later gender-critical feminists have disputed the prevalence of intersex conditions, arguing that [[Anne Fausto-Sterling]]'s estimate of 1.7% comprises mostly cases not normally considered ambiguous "in genitalia or in reproductive organs", like [[Nonclassic congenital adrenal hyperplasia|nonclassic CAH]], [[Turner syndrome]], or [[Klinefelter syndrome]].<ref name="stock_material_girls_ch2" /> Citing research showing much lower prevalence, Kathleen Stock and Holly Lawford-Smith have both argued that the existence of intersex conditions does not impact the usefulness of sex categories,<ref name="hls_what_is_gcf"/><ref name="econ_stock">{{Cite news|date=6 July 2018|title=Changing the concept of "woman" will cause unintended harms|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|url=https://www.economist.com/open-future/2018/07/06/changing-the-concept-of-woman-will-cause-unintended-harms|access-date=19 April 2019|archive-date=12 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220312004821/https://www.economist.com/open-future/2018/07/06/changing-the-concept-of-woman-will-cause-unintended-harms|url-status=live}}</ref> with Lawford-Smith saying that the term "assigned female at birth" has been "appropriated from people with differences of sexual development", and "used by trans activists for everyone, even though in more than 99% of cases, as we have seen, sex is accurately observed, not 'assigned'".<ref name="hls_what_is_gcf" />

Most intersex organizations subscribe to a mixed [[Social construction of gender|sociological perspective of sex and gender]], and as trans legislation and subjects overlaps heavily with intersex legislation, intersex people are often involved in [[trans activism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://interactadvocates.org/transgender-legislation-intersex/|title=Understanding How Anti-Transgender Legislation Also Affects Intersex Kids}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/edit/10.4324/9781003206255-60/hermaphrodites-attitude-cheryl-chase|title=The Transgender Studies Reader Remix|first=Cheryl|last=Chase|chapter=Hermaphrodites with Attitude: Mapping the Emergence of Intersex Political Activism|date=14 July 2022|publisher=Routledge|doi=10.4324/9781003206255-60|isbn=9781003206255|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=28 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043411/https://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/edit/10.4324/9781003206255-60/hermaphrodites-attitude-cheryl-chase|url-status=live}}</ref> Intersex women who display a mixed sexual [[phenotype]] often face [[Violence against transgender people|attacks similar to trans people]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/most-state-bans-on-gender-affirming-care-for-trans-youth-still-allow-controversial-intersex-surgery|title=Most state bans on gender-affirming care for trans youth still allow controversial intersex surgery|date=23 March 2023|website=PBS NewsHour}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/10/26/us-anti-trans-bills-also-harm-intersex-children|title=US: Anti-Trans Bills Also Harm Intersex Children|date=26 October 2022|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=28 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828040732/https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/10/26/us-anti-trans-bills-also-harm-intersex-children|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Sexual orientation===
{{see also|Transphobia#Gay and lesbian communities|Feminist views on sexual orientation}}

Gender critical feminists believe that transgender rights are a threat to the rights of gay people.<ref name="Lamble">{{Cite journal |last=Lamble |first=Sarah |date=2024-05-23 |title=Confronting complex alliances: Situating Britain's gender critical politics within the wider transnational anti-gender movement |journal=Journal of Lesbian Studies |volume=28 |issue=3 |language=en |pages=504–517 |doi=10.1080/10894160.2024.2356496 |pmid=38783535 |issn=1089-4160|doi-access=free }}</ref> Gender critical lesbians and feminists are a minority in the UK: polls show that cisgender lesbians and bisexual women are among the most trans-inclusive groups in Britain.<ref name="Lamble"/>

[[Kathleen Stock]], for instance, has said that allowing trans women to call themselves women "threatens a secure understanding of the concept 'lesbian{{' "}}.<ref name="econ_stock" /> [[Magdalen Berns]], co-founder of the group [[For Women Scotland]], has said that "there is no such thing as a lesbian with a penis" in regards to the idea of some trans women being lesbians.<ref>{{Cite news |work=PinkNews |url=https://www.thepinknews.com/2019/06/25/jk-rowling-under-fire-following-transphobe-twitter/ |date=June 25, 2019 |title=JK Rowling under fire for following a 'proud transphobe' on Twitter |access-date=1 January 2024 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828040810/https://www.thepinknews.com/2019/06/25/jk-rowling-under-fire-following-transphobe-twitter/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Julie Bindel]] has said that transgender women cannot be lesbians, instead qualifying them as straight men trying to "join the club", and has compared transgender activism to men sexually assaulting lesbian women for rejecting their advances.<ref>{{Cite news |work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/10/13/trans-lesbians-women-men-bearded-united-nations/ |date=Oct 13, 2023 |title=No, United Nations. 'Trans lesbians' are not lesbians |access-date=1 January 2024 |archive-date=1 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240101190304/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/10/13/trans-lesbians-women-men-bearded-united-nations/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/lesbians-are-being-erased-by-transgender-activists/ |work= The Spectator |title= Lesbians are being erased by transgender activists |access-date= 1 January 2024 |archive-date= 9 December 2023 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20231209162234/https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/lesbians-are-being-erased-by-transgender-activists/ |url-status= live }}</ref>

Many other gender critical groups and pundits have spoken of the transgender rights movement as a men's sexual rights movement, designed to pressure lesbians into having sex with trans women.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-57853385.amp |work= BBC |title= The lesbians who feel pressured to have sex and relationships with trans women |access-date= 4 January 2024 |archive-date= 28 August 2024 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20240828040736/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-57853385.amp |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|work= Cosmopolitan|url= https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/love-sex/relationships/a28935330/terf-meaning/|title= What everyone needs to know about TERFs|date= 20 September 2019|access-date= 4 January 2024|archive-date= 28 August 2024|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20240828041238/https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/love-sex/relationships/a28935330/terf-meaning/|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |work=NBC |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/amp/ncna958456 |title='Pro-lesbian' or 'trans-exclusionary'? Old animosities boil into public view |access-date=4 January 2024 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828041239/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/amp/ncna958456 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Blanchard's transsexualism typology|Ray Blanchard's theory of autogynephilia]] is a recurrent talking point in TERF discourse, where it is usually presented as established science. It characterises trans women's gender identities as caused by sexual orientation or [[sexual deviance]].<ref name=":9" /> The theory has never received wide acceptance in sexology or psychology.<ref name=":9">{{Cite journal |last=Serano |first=Julia |date=2020-08-10 |title=Autogynephilia: A scientific review, feminist analysis, and alternative 'embodiment fantasies' model |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0038026120934690 |journal=The Sociological Review |language=en |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=763–778 |doi=10.1177/0038026120934690 |issn=0038-0261 |access-date=31 July 2024 |archive-date=21 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220921214340/https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0038026120934690 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Conversion therapy===
{{See also|Conversion therapy}}
Kathleen Stock has argued that definitions of conversion therapy and bans against it should not include [[Conversion therapy#Gender identity change efforts (GICE)|gender identity conversion therapy]] on the basis that it risks criminalising "proper therapeutic exploration",<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stock |first1=Kathleen |title=An exercise in talking shop |url=https://thecritic.co.uk/an-exercise-in-talking-shop/ |website=The Critic |date=14 December 2021 |access-date=23 January 2024 |archive-date=23 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240123174641/https://thecritic.co.uk/an-exercise-in-talking-shop/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and that she believes it comes into conflict with bans against [[Sexual orientation change efforts|sexual orientation conversion therapy]].<ref name="Zanghellini">{{Cite journal |last=Zanghellini |first=Aleardo |year=2020 |title=Philosophical Problems With the Gender-Critical Feminist Argument Against Trans Inclusion |journal=SAGE Open |language=en |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=215824402092702 |doi=10.1177/2158244020927029 |issn=2158-2440 |doi-access=free }}</ref> This latter argument has been criticized on the basis that doctors affirming transgender youth do not attempt to alter [[sexual orientation]], which is understood to define who they are attracted to, and respect the person's expressed gender identity and sexual orientation.<ref name="Zanghellini" /> Gender-critical campaign groups in the United Kingdom such as Sex Matters have described the provision of gender-affirming care for transgender youth as "modern conversion therapy" which erases gay identities and argued it should be criminalized.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garton-Crosbie |first1=Abbi |title=What will a 'conversion therapy' ban in Scotland look like and who opposes it? |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/24041064.conversion-therapy-ban-scotland-will-look-like-opposes/ |access-date=23 January 2024 |work=The National |date=2024-01-10 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043415/https://www.thenational.scot/news/24041064.conversion-therapy-ban-scotland-will-look-like-opposes/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Daniel |title=Telling children they can change sex is conversion therapy, say campaigners |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/10/25/telling-children-they-can-change-sex-conversion-therapy/ |access-date=23 January 2024 |work=The Telegraph |date=2023-10-25 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828041244/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/10/25/telling-children-they-can-change-sex-conversion-therapy/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Perry |first1=Sophie |title=Westminster conversion therapy debate descends into scare-mongering about 'transing away the gay' |url=https://www.thepinknews.com/2023/12/06/westminster-conversion-therapy-trans-debate-joanna-cherry-neale-hanvey/ |access-date=23 January 2024 |work=Pink News |date=2023-12-06 |archive-date=23 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240123174640/https://www.thepinknews.com/2023/12/06/westminster-conversion-therapy-trans-debate-joanna-cherry-neale-hanvey/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Trans-exclusionary radical feminists in France campaigned against a ban on conversion therapy arguing that most transgender teenagers assigned female at birth aren't really trans.<ref name="Fassin">{{Cite journal |last=Fassin |first=Éric |date=2023-12-11 |title=An Epidemic of Transphobia on French Turf |url=https://www.digest.ugent.be/article/id/90002/ |journal=DiGeSt - Journal of Diversity and Gender Studies |volume=10 |issue=2 |doi=10.21825/digest.90002 |issn=2593-0281 |doi-access=free |access-date=23 January 2024 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043415/https://www.digest.ugent.be/article/id/90002/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In March 2022, gender-critical groups campaigned to have the UK government remove gender identity change efforts from a [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom#Conversion therapy|proposed ban on conversion therapy]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2024}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gallagher |first1=Sophie |last2=Parry |first2=Josh |title=Conversion therapy: Ban to go ahead but not cover trans people |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-60947028 |access-date=16 October 2024 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=31 March 2022 |quote=Some gender critical groups had fought for the ban not to include conversion therapy experienced by transgender people.}}</ref>

The [[Trevor Project]] and [[International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association]] have stated "gender critical therapy" is another name for conversion therapy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetrevorproject.org/get-involved/trevor-advocacy/50-bills-50-states/about-conversion-therapy/|title=About Conversion Therapy|website=The Trevor Project|access-date=5 June 2024}}</ref><ref name="ILGA">{{Cite report |url=https://www.ohchr.org/sites/default/files/Documents/Issues/SexualOrientation/IESOGI/CSOsAJ/ILGA_World_Curbing_Deception_world_survey_legal_restrictions_conversion_therapy.pdf |title=Curbing Deception: A world survey on legal regulation of so-called "conversion therapies" |last=Ramon Mendos |first=Luca |date=2020 |publisher=International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association}}</ref> Heron Greenesmith has reported on gender critical boards sharing lists of therapists whose end goal is the rejection of trans identity for parents of trans youth.<ref name="Greenesmith">{{Cite news |last=Greenesmith |first=Heron |date=2020-06-17 |title=Non-Affirming Therapists Endanger Trans Youth |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/gender-critical-support-board-trans-youth |access-date=2024-01-20 |work=Teen Vogue |language=en-US |archive-date=22 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230822184401/https://www.teenvogue.com/story/gender-critical-support-board-trans-youth |url-status=live }}</ref> The gender-critical group [[Genspect]] promotes "gender exploratory therapy", which is also considered to be [[Conversion therapy#Gender exploratory therapy|a form of conversion therapy]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Lawson |first1=Zazie |last2=Davies |first2=Skye |last3=Harmon |first3=Shae |last4=Williams |first4=Matthew |last5=Billawa |first5=Shradha |last6=Holmes |first6=Ryan |last7=Huckridge |first7=Jaymie |last8=Kelly |first8=Phillip |last9=MacIntyre-Harrison |first9=Jess |last10=Neill |first10=Stewart |last11=Song-Chase |first11=Angela |last12=Ward |first12=Hannah |last13=Yates |first13=Michael |date=October 2023 |title=A human rights based approach to transgender and gender expansive health |url=https://explore.bps.org.uk/lookup/doi/10.53841/bpscpf.2023.1.369.91 |journal=Clinical Psychology Forum |language=en |volume=1 |issue=369 |pages=91–106 |doi=10.53841/bpscpf.2023.1.369.91 |issn=1747-5732 |s2cid=265086908 |access-date=25 August 2024 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043417/https://explore.bps.org.uk/content/bpscpf/1/369/91 |url-status=live }}</ref> They argue that transgender identities stem from unprocessed trauma, childhood abuse, internalized homophobia or misogyny, sexual fetishism, and autism.<ref name="Santoro">{{Cite news |last=Santoro |first=Helen |date=2023-05-02 |title=How Therapists Are Trying to Convince Children That They're Not Actually Trans |url=https://slate.com/technology/2023/05/gender-exploratory-therapy-trans-kids-what-is-it.html |access-date=2024-01-20 |work=Slate |language=en-US |issn=1091-2339 |archive-date=21 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240121062936/https://slate.com/technology/2023/05/gender-exploratory-therapy-trans-kids-what-is-it.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

== History ==

=== Early history (before 2000) ===
Although trans people were active in feminist movements in the 1960s and earlier,<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10714420802306726 | doi=10.1080/10714420802306726 | title=Stray Thoughts on Transgender Feminism and the Barnard Conference on Women | year=2008 | last1=Stryker | first1=Susan | journal=The Communication Review | volume=11 | issue=3 | pages=217–218 | s2cid=145011138 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=2 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211202214504/https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10714420802306726 | url-status=live }}</ref> the 1970s saw conflict among some early [[radical feminists]] over the inclusion of trans women in feminism.<ref name="Bettcher">{{Citation|last=Bettcher|first=Talia|title=Feminist Perspectives on Trans Issues|date=2014|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2014/entries/feminism-trans/|encyclopedia=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Spring 2014|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=13 April 2019|archive-date=28 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328062920/https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2014/entries/feminism-trans/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/08/04/woman-2|title=What Is a Woman? The dispute between radical feminism and transgenderism|last=Goldberg|first=Michelle|date=5 August 2014|work=New Yorker Magazine|access-date=1 December 2019|archive-date=13 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113031943/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/08/04/woman-2|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 1973, trans-exclusionary radical feminist activists from the [[Daughters of Bilitis]] voted to expel [[Beth Elliott]], an out trans woman, from the organization.<ref name="SAGE-TERF">{{Cite encyclopedia |title=TERFs |encyclopedia=The SAGE encyclopedia of trans studies |publisher=SAGE Reference |location=London Los Angeles |last=Williams |first=Cristan |date=2021 |pages=822–825 |isbn=978-1-5443-9381-0}}</ref> The same year, Elliott was scheduled to perform at the West Coast Lesbian Conference, which she had helped organize; a group of trans-exclusionary radical feminist activists calling themselves the Gutter Dykes leafletted the conference protesting her inclusion and keynote speaker [[Robin Morgan]] updated her speech to describe Elliott as "an opportunist, an infiltrator, and a destroyer – with the mentality of a rapist".<ref name="SAGE-TERF"/><ref name="Thurlow" /><ref name="Williams 2020 pp. 718–734"/> An impromptu vote was held with the majority supporting her inclusion in the conference; when Elliott subsequently entered the stage to perform the Gutter Dykes rushed to the stage to attack her and attacked performers [[Robin Tyler]] and [[Patty Harrison]] who had stepped in to defend her.<ref name="SAGE-TERF"/><ref name="Thurlow" /><ref name="Williams 2020 pp. 718–734"/>

At the 1973 [[Christopher Street Liberation Day]] rally, trans-exclusionary radical feminists tried to stop [[Sylvia Rivera]] from speaking.<ref name="SAGE-TERF"/> [[Jean O'Leary]] publicly denounced Sylvia Rivera as "parodying womanhood" and [[Lesbian Feminist Liberation]] distributed flyers seeking to keep "female impersonators" off the stage.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gan |first=Jessi |date=2007 |title="Still at the back of the bus": Sylvia Rivera's struggle. |url=https://transreads.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/2019-03-20_5c91dd8e0c2a2_SylviaRiverainterview.pdf |journal=CENTRO Journal |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=125–139 |access-date=15 January 2024 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043413/https://transreads.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/2019-03-20_5c91dd8e0c2a2_SylviaRiverainterview.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

Trans-exclusionary radical feminist activists protested [[Sandy Stone (artist)|Sandy Stone]]'s position at [[Olivia Records]], a trans-inclusive lesbian separatist music collective. In 1977 The Gorgons, a trans-exclusionary lesbian separatist paramilitary group, issued a death threat to Stone and came to the event armed though were intercepted by security. Escalating threats against the collective motivated Stone to leave the group.<ref name="SAGE-TERF"/>

[[Janice Raymond]]'s ''[[The Transsexual Empire]]'', published in 1979, examined what she considered to be the role of transgender identity in reinforcing traditional gender stereotypes, in particular the ways in which the "medical-psychiatric complex" was medicalizing gender identity, and the social and political context that contributed to the image of gender-affirming treatment and surgery as therapeutic medicine.<ref name="Raymond 1994">{{cite book | title=The Transsexual Empire: The Making of the She-male | last=Raymond | first=Janice G. | publisher=Teachers College Press | location=New York | isbn=978-0807762721 | year=1994 | edition=2nd | url=https://janiceraymond.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/The%20Transsexual%20Empire.pdf | access-date=24 May 2019 | archive-date=8 November 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108205024/http://janiceraymond.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/The%20Transsexual%20Empire.pdf | url-status=live }}</ref> Raymond maintained that this was based in the "patriarchal myths" of "male mothering", and "making of woman according to man's image", and that transgender identity aimed "to colonize feminist identification, culture, politics and sexuality".<ref name="Raymond 1994"/> The book goes on to say that "All transsexuals [[rape]] women's bodies by reducing the real female form to an artifact" and that "the problem of transsexualism would best be served by morally mandating it out of existence".<ref>Raymond, Janice. (1994). ''The Transsexual Empire'', p. 104, 178</ref> Several authors have since characterized this work as transphobic and constituting hate speech, as well as lacking any serious intellectual basis.<ref name="Rose 2004">{{cite journal|last=Rose|first=Katrina C.|year=2004|url=http://www.ifge.org/?q=node/237|title=The Man Who Would be Janice Raymond|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329234214/http://www.ifge.org/?q=node%2F237 |archive-date=29 March 2019|journal=Transgender Tapestry|volume=104}}</ref><ref name="Namaste 2000">{{cite book|last=Namaste|first=Viviane K.|author-link=Viviane Namaste|year=2000|title=Invisible Lives: The Erasure of Transsexual and Transgendered People|pages=33–34|publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=9780226568102}}</ref><ref name="Hayes 2003">{{cite journal|last=Hayes|first=Cressida J.|author-link=Cressida Heyes|year=2003|title=Feminist Solidarity after Queer Theory: The Case of Transgender|journal=Signs|volume=28|number=4|pages=1093–1120|doi=10.1086/343132|jstor=10.1086/343132|s2cid=144107471}}</ref><ref name="Serano 2007">{{cite book|first=Julia|last=Serano|author-link=Julia Serano|year=2007|title=Whipping Girl: A Transsexual Woman on Sexism and the Scapegoating of Femininity|publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=9781580051545}}</ref>{{rp|pages=233–234}}

In 1991 Nancy Burkholder, a trans woman, was ejected from the [[Michigan Womyn's Music Festival]] (MWMF), after refusing to answer when another woman asked her whether or not she was transgender.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2000-09-12/columns/trouble-in-utopia/ |title=Trouble in Utopia |access-date=10 January 2009 |work=The Village Voice |date=12 September 2000 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115211653/http://www.villagevoice.com/2000-09-12/columns/trouble-in-utopia/ |archive-date=15 January 2009}}</ref><ref name="SAGE-TERF"/> This removal was justified by the retroactive instatement of a [[womyn-born womyn]] policy by the MWMF organisers.<ref name="Serano 2007" />{{rp|pages=233–245}} For both the 1992 and 1993 MWMF events, [[Janis Walworth]], a cisgender lesbian feminist, organised an educational and outreach program at the MWMF distributing pamphlets titled "Gender Myths".<ref name="Williams 2020 pp. 718–734">{{cite journal | last=Williams | first=Cristan | title=The ontological woman: A history of deauthentication, dehumanization, and violence | journal=The Sociological Review | volume=68 | issue=4 | date=2020 | issn=0038-0261 | doi=10.1177/0038026120938292 | pages=718–734| s2cid=221097519 }}</ref> During the 1993 MWMF event, Walworth was told by event security that she and any trans women in their group would be required to leave the event "for their own safety".<ref name="Williams 2020 pp. 718–734" /> Although an offer of bodyguard protection was provided by a group of [[Leather subculture|leather lesbians]] attending the festival, Walworth's group decided instead to set up an outreach camp outside the festival gates.<ref name="Williams 2020 pp. 718–734" /><ref name="SAGE-TERF"/> This camp, later known as [[Camp Trans]], continued to provide education and outreach attempts while protesting the festival's trans exclusionary practices until the festival's final event in 2015.<ref name="Williams 2020 pp. 718–734" /><ref name="SAGE-TERF"/>

== By country ==
{{Globalize|section|UK|Anglophone|date=July 2024|discuss=Talk:Gender-critical feminism#Globalize template}}

=== Russia ===
In Russia, trans-exclusionary feminists, who position themselves as [[radical feminism|radical]], constitute one of the two main streams of [[feminism in Russia|feminism]]. Unlike their opponents adhering to [[intersectional feminism]], the trans-exclusionary group Womenation and a number of other trans-exclusionary feminists supported the [[Russian invasion of Ukraine]] in 2022 and came into conflict with [[feminism in Ukraine|Ukrainian feminist]] movement. Vanya Mark Solovey, a gender researcher, argues that the solidarity of Russian trans-exclusionary feminists with Russian policy towards Ukraine is closely related to the anti-trans sentiments of the Russian authorities.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Solovey |first=Vanya Mark |date=2023-05-30 |title=Feminism and Aggressive Imperialism: Russian Feminist Politics in Wartime |journal={{lang|de|Femina Politica – Zeitschrift für feministische Politikwissenschaft}} |language=en |volume=32 |issue=1 |doi=10.3224/feminapolitica.v32i1.08 |issn=2196-1646 |pages=95–101 |doi-access=free}}</ref>

=== South Korea ===
In 2016, the [[radical feminist]] online community [[Womad (website)|Womad]] split from the larger radical feminist online community [[Megalia]] after Megalia issued a ban on the use of certain explicit slurs against gay men and transgender people. This change in policy led to the migration of [[anti-LGBT]] members.<ref name=":0b">{{Cite news|last=Kim|first=Ashley|date=8 September 2019|title=Womad: The New Face of Feminism in Korea?|work=[[Berkeley Political Review]]|url=https://bpr.berkeley.edu/2019/09/08/womad-the-new-face-of-feminism-in-korea/|access-date=2 October 2021|archive-date=29 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230629035406/https://bpr.berkeley.edu/2019/09/08/womad-the-new-face-of-feminism-in-korea/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In February 2020, [[Sookmyung Women's University]] accepted its first transgender student. The decision prompted a strong backlash both within and outside of the university, including from radical feminist student organizations. However, some students, and the university's Student and Minority Human Rights Commission, supported the decision.<ref name=":7">{{Cite conference |last=Bae |first=Sooyoun |date=2023-02-01 |title=Discord Between Transgender Women and TERFs in South Korea |url=https://papers.iafor.org/wp-content/uploads/papers/ace2022/ACE2022_66496.pdf |conference=The Asian Conference on Education 2022: Official Conference Proceedings |publisher=[[The International Academic Forum]] |doi=10.22492/issn.2186-5892.2023.67 |issn=2186-5892 |doi-access=free |access-date=29 June 2024 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043415/https://papers.iafor.org/wp-content/uploads/papers/ace2022/ACE2022_66496.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-02-03 |title=Sookmyung Women's University's first transgender student faces discriminations both on and off campus |url=https://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/926747 |access-date=2024-06-29 |website=[[The Hankyoreh]] |language=en |archive-date=29 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240629075724/https://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/926747 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ahn |first=Sung-mi |date=2020-02-07 |title=Transgender student withdraws after getting accepted to Sookmyung Women's University |url=https://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200207000642 |access-date=2024-06-29 |website=[[The Korea Herald]] |language=en |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043419/https://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200207000642 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Lee Hyun-Jae has noted that in the South Korean "[[feminism reboot]]" of the early 21st century, the radical stance of recent feminists have been "oriented in an [[identity politics]] based on [[biological sex]]", and that "the radical stance of today's [young] feminists has a tendency to emphasize the identity of the 'female body' as based on the category of the 'biological woman,' taking an attitude of excluding 'biological' men refugees, and transgender people".<ref name=":4" /> Jinsook Kim has noted that "in Korean contexts, there have been increasing concerns over popular forms of feminism based on a strong female identity rooted in notions of biological sex, the pursuit of female-only and -first politics, and the refusal of solidarity with other social minority groups".<ref name=":6">{{Cite journal |last=Kim |first=Jinsook |date=December 2021 |title=The Resurgence and Popularization of Feminism in South Korea: Key Issues and Challenges for Contemporary Feminist Activism |journal=[[Korea Journal]] |volume=61 |issue=4 |pages=75–101 |doi=10.25024/kj.2021.61.4.75 |doi-access=free}}</ref>

=== United Kingdom ===
{{see also|21st century anti-trans movement in the United Kingdom}}
{{very long section|date=August 2024}}

In 2016, the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]' [[Women and Equalities Committee]] issued a report recommending that the [[Gender Recognition Act 2004]] be updated "in line with the principles of [[gender self-declaration]]".<ref>{{cite report|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmselect/cmwomeq/390/39010.htm#_idTextAnchor213|title=Transgender Equality|last1=Women and Equalities Committee|date=8 January 2016|publisher=House of Commons|quote=Within the current Parliament, the Government must bring forward proposals to update the Gender Recognition Act, in line with the principles of gender self-declaration that have been developed in other jurisdictions. In place of the present medicalised, quasi-judicial application process, an administrative process must be developed, centred on the wishes of the individual applicant, rather than on intensive analysis by doctors and lawyers.|access-date=1 November 2021|archive-date=28 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043421/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmselect/cmwomeq/390/39010.htm#_idTextAnchor213|url-status=live}}</ref> Later in 2016, in [[England and Wales]], a proposal was developed under [[Theresa May]]'s government to revise the Act to introduce self-identification, with a public consultation opening in 2018. This proposed reform became a key locus of conflict for the emerging gender-critical movement, seeking to block reform of the Act, with a number of groups such as [[Fair Play For Women]], [[For Women Scotland]], and [[Woman's Place UK]] being formed. 2018 found a significant majority of respondents in favour of the GRA reforms,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/response-to-the-gender-recognition-act-2004-consultation |title=Reform of the Gender Recognition Act — Analysis of consultation responses |first1=Daniel |last1=King |author2=Carrie Paechter |author3=Maranda Ridgway |publisher=[[Her Majesty's Stationery Office]] |date=22 September 2020 |access-date=21 October 2021 |id=CP&nbsp;294 |pages=8–9 |archive-date=5 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201005045042/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/response-to-the-gender-recognition-act-2004-consultation |url-status=live }}</ref> however, in 2020, [[Second Johnson ministry|Boris Johnson's government]] dropped the reforms, instead reducing the cost of a gender recognition certificate and moving the application process online.

Another key locus of conflict for the emerging movement was the stance of LGBT rights charity [[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] on trans issues. In 2015, Stonewall had begun campaigning for trans equality, with Stonewall head [[Ruth Hunt]] apologising for the organisation's previous failure to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gani|first1=Aisha|title=Stonewall to start campaigning for trans equality|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/feb/16/stonewall-start-campaigning-trans-equality|access-date=31 May 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426042549/http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/feb/16/stonewall-start-campaigning-trans-equality|archive-date=26 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, the [[LGB Alliance]] was founded in opposition to Stonewall, accusing the organization of having "undermined women's sex-based rights and protections" and attempting "to introduce confusion between biological sex and the notion of gender".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hellen |first=Nicholas |date=22 September 2019 |title='Anti-women' trans policy may split Stonewall |work=The Sunday Times |location=London |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/anti-women-trans-policy-may-split-stonewall-wfv2rp5cx |access-date=13 February 2021 |archive-date=1 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201130445/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/anti-women-trans-policy-may-split-stonewall-wfv2rp5cx |url-status=live }}</ref>

The year 2019 saw the formation of the [[Women's Human Rights Campaign]] (now Women's Declaration International) by noted gender-critical feminist [[Sheila Jeffreys]] and co-founder Heather Brunskell-Evans. The group published a manifesto titled the ''Declaration on Women's Sex-Based Rights'', which argued that recognising trans women as women "constitutes discrimination against women" and called for the "elimination of that act".<ref>{{cite news |title=MPs urged by anti-trans 'women's rights' group to eliminate 'transgenderism' and scrap Gender Recognition Act |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/01/27/womens-human-rights-campaign-gender-recognition-act-inquiry-trans-transphobia/ |access-date=2 December 2021 |work=[[Pink News]] |archive-date=22 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220922041648/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/01/27/womens-human-rights-campaign-gender-recognition-act-inquiry-trans-transphobia/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.womensdeclaration.com/en/declaration-womens-sex-based-rights-full-text/ | title=Declaration on Women's Sex-Based Rights: Full Text - Women's Declaration International | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=7 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207043837/https://womensdeclaration.com/en/declaration-womens-sex-based-rights-full-text/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:J. K. Rowling 2010.jpg|thumb|[[J. K. Rowling]] is a prominent gender-critical feminist in the United Kingdom.|left|200x200px]]

A 2020 paper in [[SAGE Open]] said that "the case against trans inclusion in the United Kingdom has been presented primarily through social media and blog-type or journalistic online platforms lacking the traditional prepublication checks of academic peer review".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zanghellini |first1=Aleardo |title=Philosophical Problems With the Gender-Critical Feminist Argument Against Trans Inclusion |journal=SAGE Open |date=1 April 2020 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=2158244020927029 |doi=10.1177/2158244020927029 |s2cid=219733494 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Some public figures such as [[Graham Linehan]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/11/12/gender-critical-coming-out-day-trans-graham-linehan-mumsnet/ | title=A so-called 'gender critical coming out day' for TERFs sparks blistering backlash | date=12 November 2021 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208221551/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/11/12/gender-critical-coming-out-day-trans-graham-linehan-mumsnet/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://gcn.ie/graham-linehan-trans-conversion-therapy/ | title=Graham Linehan calls for list of Irish 'gender critical' therapists for trans children | date=5 February 2020 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=5 March 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220305195408/https://gcn.ie/graham-linehan-trans-conversion-therapy/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/06/27/entertainment/graham-linehan-twitter-removal-trnd/index.html | title=Graham Linehan, creator of 'The IT Crowd' and 'Father Ted,' has been removed from Twitter | date=27 June 2020 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208221549/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/06/27/entertainment/graham-linehan-twitter-removal-trnd/index.html | url-status=live }}</ref> and [[J. K. Rowling]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/06/10/entertainment/jk-rowling/index.html | title=J.K. Rowling explains her gender identity views in essay amid backlash | website=[[CNN]] | date=10 June 2020 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=24 November 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211124202606/https://www.cnn.com/2020/06/10/entertainment/jk-rowling/index.html | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/jun/11/why-is-jk-rowling-speaking-out-now-on-sex-and-gender-debate | title=Why is JK Rowling speaking out now on sex and gender debate? | newspaper=The Guardian | date=11 June 2020 | last1=Brooks | first1=Libby | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=9 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211209194802/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/jun/11/why-is-jk-rowling-speaking-out-now-on-sex-and-gender-debate | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/columnists/why-feminists-like-me-stand-with-jk-rowling-in-trans-rights-row-susan-dalgety-2910085|title=Why feminists like me stand with JK Rowling in trans rights row – Susan Dalgety &#124; The Scotsman|access-date=8 December 2021|archive-date=8 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208221551/https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/columnists/why-feminists-like-me-stand-with-jk-rowling-in-trans-rights-row-susan-dalgety-2910085|url-status=live}}</ref> have often been featured in gender-critical social media posts. The Internet forum [[Mumsnet]] has also been a prominent hub of online gender-critical discourse.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jun/13/mumsnet-transgender-row-feminism-tougher-forum-rules | title=Mumsnet brings in tougher forum rules after transgender row | newspaper=The Guardian | date=13 June 2018 | last1=Ntim | first1=Zac | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208221550/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jun/13/mumsnet-transgender-row-feminism-tougher-forum-rules | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/mumsnet-moderators-trans-rights-debate | title=Mumsnet moderators are struggling to find the line between free speech and transphobia | magazine=Wired UK | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208221549/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/mumsnet-moderators-trans-rights-debate | url-status=live }}</ref>

Gender-critical views are common in the British media.<ref name="Burns 2019"/><ref name="cnn_uk_media">{{cite web | url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/09/uk/uk-trans-rights-gender-critical-media-intl-gbr-cmd/index.html | title=Anti-trans rhetoric is rife in the British media. Little is being done to extinguish the flames | website=[[CNN]] | date=9 October 2021 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=11 March 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311180308/https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/09/uk/uk-trans-rights-gender-critical-media-intl-gbr-cmd/index.html | url-status=live }}</ref> The British press frequently publishes articles critical of trans people and trans issues.<ref name="cnn_uk_media" />  In 2018, the US version of ''The Guardian'' published an editorial condemning an editorial in the UK version of ''The Guardian'' for transphobia, because it portrayed trans rights as being opposed to the rights of cis women.<ref name="us_guardian_response">{{cite news|last1=Levin|first1=Sam|last2=Chalabi|first2=Mona|last3=Siddiqui|first3=Sabrina|date=2 November 2018|title=Why we take issue with the Guardian's stance on trans rights in the UK|language=en-GB|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/nov/02/guardian-editorial-response-transgender-rights-uk|access-date=14 May 2019|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=23 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523043608/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/nov/02/guardian-editorial-response-transgender-rights-uk|url-status=live}}</ref> Drawing on theory of [[radicalization]], Craig McLean argues that discourse on transgender-related issues in the UK has been radicalized in response to the activities of what he terms the anti-transgender movement that pushes "a radical agenda to deny the basic rights of trans people (...) under the cover of 'free speech'".<ref>{{cite journal |author-last1=McLean |author-first1=Craig |title=The Growth of the Anti-Transgender Movement in the United Kingdom. The Silent Radicalization of the British Electorate |journal=International Journal of Sociology |date=2021 |volume=51 |issue=6 |pages=473–482 |doi=10.1080/00207659.2021.1939946 |s2cid=237874806 |url=http://nrl.northumbria.ac.uk/id/eprint/46370/9/The%20Growth%20of%20the%20Anti%20Transgender%20Movement%20in%20the%20United%20Kingdom%20The%20Silent%20Radicalization%20of%20the%20British%20Electorate.pdf |access-date=28 June 2023 |archive-date=14 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211214191327/https://nrl.northumbria.ac.uk/id/eprint/46370/9/The%20Growth%20of%20the%20Anti%20Transgender%20Movement%20in%20the%20United%20Kingdom%20The%20Silent%20Radicalization%20of%20the%20British%20Electorate.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

In Resolution 2417 (2022), the [[Council of Europe]] condemned "the highly prejudicial anti-gender, gender-critical and anti-trans narratives which reduce the fight for the equality of LGBTI people to what these movements deliberately mischaracterise as 'gender ideology' or 'LGBTI ideology'. Such narratives deny the very existence of LGBTI people, dehumanise them, and often falsely portray their rights as being in conflict with women's and children's rights, or societal and family values in general. All of these are deeply damaging to LGBTI people, while also harming women's and children's rights and social cohesion". The resolution further deplored "the extensive and often virulent attacks on the rights of LGBTI people that have been occurring for several years in, among other countries, Hungary, Poland, the Russian Federation, Turkey and the United Kingdom".<ref name=Resolution2417>{{cite web |title=Resolution 2417 (2022): Combating rising hate against LGBTI people in Europe |url=https://pace.coe.int/en/files/29712/html |date=25 January 2022 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=28 June 2023 |archive-date=19 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221119052750/https://pace.coe.int/en/files/29712/html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Duffy |first=Nick |date=25 January 2022 |title=Council of Europe condemns 'virulent attacks on LGBT rights' in the UK, Hungary and Poland |work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/world/council-of-europe-condemns-virulent-attacks-on-lgbt-rights-uk-1423399 |access-date=30 January 2022 |archive-date=30 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130182653/https://inews.co.uk/news/world/council-of-europe-condemns-virulent-attacks-on-lgbt-rights-uk-1423399 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Council of Europe compares UK to Russia and Poland over 'virulent attacks' on LGBT+ rights |url=https://www.thepinknews.com/2022/01/25/council-of-europe-uk-lgbt-trans-rights-russ-apoland/ |access-date=28 June 2023 |work=PinkNews |archive-date=30 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230530233726/https://www.thepinknews.com/2022/01/25/council-of-europe-uk-lgbt-trans-rights-russ-apoland/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

====Sex-based rights====
The term "sex-based rights" is used, primarily in the UK, to refer to a variety of legal positions and political objectives, including:

* Existing exceptions defined in the UK [[Equality Act 2010]]. These exceptions do not grant any right for individuals to be offered single-sex services, but do allow service providers to offer such services, if they are "a proportionate means of achieving a legitimate aim".<ref>{{cite web |title=Attorney General affirms sex-based rights |url=https://womansplaceuk.org/2022/08/11/attorney-general-affirms-sex-based-rights/ |website=Woman's Place UK |date=11 August 2022 |access-date=17 August 2023 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042323/https://womansplaceuk.org/2022/08/11/attorney-general-affirms-sex-based-rights/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Gender reassignment provisions in the Equality Act |url=https://www.equalityhumanrights.com/en/advice-and-guidance/gender-reassignment-provisions-equality-act |website=Equality and Human Rights Commission |access-date=11 September 2023 |archive-date=29 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929192108/https://www.equalityhumanrights.com/en/advice-and-guidance/gender-reassignment-provisions-equality-act |url-status=dead }}</ref>
* Proposed changes to the Equality Act to clarify sex as meaning biological sex<ref>{{cite news |last1=Allegretti |first1=Aubrey |title=What would changing the Equality Act mean for trans people and single-sex spaces? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2023/apr/05/what-would-changing-the-equality-act-mean-for-trans-people-and-single-sex-spaces |access-date=17 August 2023 |work=The Guardian |date=5 April 2023 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042324/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2023/apr/05/what-would-changing-the-equality-act-mean-for-trans-people-and-single-sex-spaces |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Clarifying the definition of 'sex' in the Equality Act {{!}} EHRC |url=https://www.equalityhumanrights.com/media-centre/news/clarifying-definition-sex-equality-act |access-date=2024-07-07 |website=www.equalityhumanrights.com |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042325/https://www.equalityhumanrights.com/media-centre/news/clarifying-definition-sex-equality-act |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-06-03 |title=Tories pledge to tackle 'confusion' over legal definition of sex |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c0kkvkkejgno |access-date=2024-07-07 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref>
* The belief that sex is central to the definition of women and women's rights, as opposed to basing law on gender identity.<ref name="scotsman">{{cite news |title=Women's rights declaration sparks accusations of discrimination|date=6 November 2019 |last=Davidson |first=Gina |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/womens-rights-declaration-sparks-accusations-discrimination-2509098 |access-date=3 December 2021 |work=[[The Scotsman]] |archive-date=3 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211203153708/https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/womens-rights-declaration-sparks-accusations-discrimination-2509098 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The gender-critical movement argues that recognition of transgender women as women conflicts with these rights.<ref name="trans_inclusive_criminology">{{cite journal | url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10612-021-09590-0 | doi=10.1007/s10612-021-09590-0 | title=Building an Intersectional and Trans-Inclusive Criminology: Responding to the Emergence of "Gender Critical" Perspectives in Feminist Criminology | year=2021 | last1=Valcore | first1=Jace | last2=Fradella | first2=Henry F. | last3=Guadalupe-Diaz | first3=Xavier | last4=Ball | first4=Matthew J. | last5=Dwyer | first5=Angela | last6=Dejong | first6=Christina | last7=Walker | first7=Allyn | last8=Wodda | first8=Aimee | last9=Worthen | first9=Meredith G. F. | journal=Critical Criminology | volume=29 | issue=4 | pages=687–706 | s2cid=244192331 | access-date=7 December 2021 | archive-date=7 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207212229/https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10612-021-09590-0 | url-status=live }}</ref>
<!-- unsourced, and seems redundant : Disagreements arise amongst feminists and trans-exclusionary feminists, as the inclusion/exclusion of transgender women polarizes both parties. There is debate if the inclusion of transgender women in feminism harvests a stronger and inclusive community, or if further oppresses cis-gender women. -->

====Legal cases====
In 2019, the ''[[Maya Forstater v Centre for Global Development]]'' tribunal case was launched by [[Maya Forstater]], crowdfunding over £120,000. Earlier that year, Forstater's consulting contract for the [[Center for Global Development|Centre for Global Development]] was not renewed after she made a number of social media posts saying that men cannot change into women.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 December 2019 |title=Researcher who lost job for tweeting 'men cannot change into women' loses employment tribunal |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/maya-forstater-transgender-test-case-equalities-act-employment-tribunal-a9253211.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220422044712/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/maya-forstater-transgender-test-case-equalities-act-employment-tribunal-a9253211.html |archive-date=22 April 2022 |access-date=30 January 2021 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref> Forstater subsequently sued the centre, alleging that she had been discriminated against because of her views.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gordon |first=Jane |date=23 April 2021 |title='I am fighting for the right to say men can never be women' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/amfightingfor-therightto-saymen-cannever-bewomen// |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220212191006/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/amfightingfor-therightto-saymen-cannever-bewomen/ |archive-date=12 February 2022 |access-date=23 April 2021 |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> Forstater lost her initial case, with the judge ruling that her beliefs were not protected under the [[Equality Act 2010|Equality Act]] due to their absolutism. However, in April 2021, the initial judgement was reversed, with the [[Employment Appeal Tribunal]] ruling that gender-critical beliefs were protected under the Equality Act.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cross |first1=Michael |title=Appeal backs woman over 'transphobic tweets' 10 June 2021 |url=https://www.lawgazette.co.uk/law/appeal-backs-woman-over-transphobic-tweets/5108799.article |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210617102834/https://www.lawgazette.co.uk/law/appeal-backs-woman-over-transphobic-tweets/5108799.article |archive-date=17 June 2021 |access-date=17 June 2021 |website=lawgazette |publisher=Law Society Gazette}}</ref> A full merits hearing on Forstater's claim that she lost her employment as a result of these beliefs was heard in March 2022, and the decision, delivered in July 2022, was that Forstater had been subjected to direct discrimination and victimisation because of her gender-critical beliefs.<ref>{{cite news |date=6 July 2022 |title=Maya Forstater: Woman discriminated against over trans tweets, tribunal rules |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-62061929 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230312113158/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-62061929 |archive-date=12 March 2023 |access-date=25 June 2023 |work=BBC News}}</ref>

In October 2020, Ann Sinnott, at the time a director of the [[LGB Alliance]], initiated a legal case calling for a judicial review of the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]]'s guidance on the [[Equality Act 2010]], crowdfunding almost £100,000 for legal fees. In May 2021 the case was found by the court to be unarguable, Justice Henshaw stating that "the claimant has shown no arguable reason to believe the Code has misled or will mislead service providers about their responsibilities under the Act".<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 May 2021 |title=Judge throws out LGB Alliance founder's fight to ban trans women from women's spaces |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/05/06/lgb-alliance-ann-sinnott-judicial-review-fails-london-high-court-equality-act/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221125215758/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/05/06/lgb-alliance-ann-sinnott-judicial-review-fails-london-high-court-equality-act/ |archive-date=25 November 2022 |access-date=10 May 2021 |website=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>

The ''Forstater'' case has been used as a precedent for several claims of discrimination against people holding gender-critical views. Employment tribunals have delivered successful judgements in cases against [[Allison Bailey|a barrister's chambers]], [[Arts Council England]], [[Westminster City Council|Westminster Council]] and Social Work England. Claims against [[Girlguiding|Girlguiding UK]] and [[United Kingdom Council for Psychotherapy]] ended in settlements, while a claim against the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] failed after the claimant was deemed to have gone too far by misgendering service users. The barrister Georgiana Calvert-Lee commented to the ''Guardian'': "Above all, in a pluralistic society, which is what we want, you have to accept that people are going to have different views."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Siddique |first1=Haroon |date=19 January 2024 |title=A politically toxic issue': the legal battles over gender-critical beliefs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/jan/19/a-politically-toxic-issue-the-legal-battles-over-gender-critical-beliefs |access-date=19 January 2023 |website=theguardian.com |publisher=Guardian |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042827/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/jan/19/a-politically-toxic-issue-the-legal-battles-over-gender-critical-beliefs |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2024, [[Jo Phoenix]] was successful in a claim against the [[Open University]] for discrimination on the grounds of gender-critical beliefs. The tribunal ruled that she had been constructively unfairly dismissed, and that she had suffered victimisation and harassment in the form of an open letter from 386 of her colleagues, as well as individual disparagement for her views, including one professor comparing her to "the racist uncle at the Christmas table".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Siddique |first1=Haroon |date=22 January 2024 |title=Open University academic wins tribunal case over gender-critical views |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/jan/22/open-university-academic-wins-tribunal-case-over-gender-critical-views |access-date=24 January 2024 |website=theguardian.com |publisher=Guardian |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828042828/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/jan/22/open-university-academic-wins-tribunal-case-over-gender-critical-views |url-status=live }}</ref>

In August 2024, [[Cambridgeshire County Council]] conceded that it had discriminated against Lizzie Pitt, a social worker, by initiating a disciplinary process against her following her gender-critical statements made at an LGBT support group. Pitt described the concession as a "win for the right side of history". The council admitted liability and agreed to pay compensation of £54,000.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Henderson |first=Cameron |date=2024-08-02 |title=Council admits discriminating against social worker over her gender-critical views |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2024/08/02/cambridgeshire-council-discrimination-social-worker-gender/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240802223043/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2024/08/02/cambridgeshire-council-discrimination-social-worker-gender/ |archive-date=2024-08-02 |access-date=2024-08-10 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |language=en-GB |issn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Moss |first1=Rob |title=Judge urges council to mandate 'freedom of belief' training|date=17 September 2024 |url=https://www.personneltoday.com/hr/freedom-of-belief-training-gender-fluid-dachshund-pitt-v-cambridgeshire-county-council/ |website=personneltoday.com |publisher=Personnel Today |access-date=19 September 2024}}</ref>

In August 2024, a private settlement was reached between the Metanoia Institute and student psychotherapist James Esses. In a statement released following the settlement, the Metanoia Institute stated that it failed to follow its processes in not affording Esses a hearing prior to his expulsion after he expressed his gender-critical views and campaigned against a proposed ban on [[conversion therapy]]. In the statement, the institute apologized for publicizing the expulsion on social media.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gentleman |first=Amelia |date=2024-08-15 |title=Student psychotherapist wins apology over expulsion for gender-critical views |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/article/2024/aug/15/student-psychotherapist-wins-apology-over-expulsion-for-gender-critical-views |access-date=2024-08-19 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=28 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240828043019/https://www.theguardian.com/society/article/2024/aug/15/student-psychotherapist-wins-apology-over-expulsion-for-gender-critical-views |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metanoia.ac.uk/about/litigation-with-james-esses/|title=Litigation with James Esses|date=15 August 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240821060610/https://www.metanoia.ac.uk/about/litigation-with-james-esses/|archive-date=21 August 2024|url-status=dead|access-date=21 September 2024}}</ref>

=== United States ===
Although gender-critical feminism originated in the United States in the 1970s, it has largely fallen out of favor among American feminists.<ref name="Burns 2019"/> Some gender-critical organizations do remain, however, such as [[WoLF]], a gender-critical feminist organization that operates mainly within the United States.<ref name="Burns 2019" />

== Analysis ==

=== Scholarly analysis ===
[[Lesbian studies]] scholars Carly Thomsen and Laurie Essig note that "transness has been and is the object of deep hostility within some marginalized forms of feminism. Skepticism among earlier anti-trans feminists, such as Janice Raymond, about trans women being "real" women has morphed into J.K. Rowling's Twitter feed where she has insisted that trans women are not women. These ideas are, of course, deplorable, but they are also quite fringe within feminist studies and activism in the US".<ref name=Thomsen>{{cite journal |last1=Thomsen |first1=Carly |last2=Essig |first2=Laurie |title=Lesbian, feminist, TERF: a queer attack on feminist studies |journal=[[Journal of Lesbian Studies]] |date=2021 |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=27–44 |doi=10.1080/10894160.2021.1950270|pmid=34313195 |s2cid=236452285 }}</ref>

Clair Thurlow notes that the more explicitly hateful language used by early trans-exclusionary radical feminists failed to gain support, forcing them to pivot towards euphemisms and [[dog-whistle politics|dog-whistle]]s such as using "pro-woman" to mean "anti-trans", "protecting sex-based rights" meant excluding trans people, and "trans-exclusionary radical feminism" became "gender-critical feminism". This allowed trans-exclusionary feminism to appear reasonable to the average person while maintaining their anti-trans meanings to other anti-trans activists.<ref name=Thurlow/>

Gender studies scholars Serena Bassi and Greta LaFleur have noted that TERFism started out as a fringe group among English speaking [[cultural feminism|cultural feminists]] in the 1970s that grew rapidly due to media exposure.<ref name=Bassi>{{cite journal |last1=Bassi |first1=Serena |last2=LaFleur |first2=Greta |title=Introduction: TERFs, Gender-Critical Movements, and Postfascist Feminisms |journal=[[Transgender Studies Quarterly]] |date=2022 |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=311–333 |doi=10.1215/23289252-9836008|s2cid=253052875 |doi-access=free }}</ref>

Cristan Williams notes that radical feminism has historically been predominantly trans-inclusive and considers trans-exclusionary views a minority or fringe view within radical feminism.<ref name=Williams>{{cite journal |last1=Williams |first1=Cristan |title=Radical Inclusion: Recounting the Trans Inclusive History of Radical Feminism |journal=Transgender Studies Quarterly |date=2016 |volume=3 |issue=1–2 |pages=254–258 |doi=10.1215/23289252-3334463|doi-access=free }}</ref>

Carrera-Fernández and DePalma argued that "the increasingly belligerent popular discourses promoted by TERF groups since the 1970s [are] appropriating feminist discourses to produce arguments that contradict basic premises of feminism".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carrera-Fernández |first1=María Victoria |last2=DePalma |first2=Renée |title=Feminism will be trans-inclusive or it will not be: Why do two cis-hetero woman educators support transfeminism? |journal=[[The Sociological Review]] |date=2020 |volume=68 |issue=4 |pages=745–762 |doi=10.1177/0038026120934686|s2cid=221097541 }}</ref>

[[Henry F. Fradella]] said that most contemporary feminists are supportive of trans people, and that gender-critical feminists are a small but vocal group who believe that trans rights threaten the rights of cis women. Most gender-critical arguments for this belief, he says, are false, and "misconstrue or ignore empirical data from both the natural and social sciences". Gender-critical feminism risks legal equality and contributes to criminalization of trans people.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fradella |first1=Henry F.|author-link=Henry F. Fradella |title=The Imperative of Rejecting 'Gender-Critical' Feminism in the Law |journal=William & Mary Journal of Race, Gender, & Social Justice |date=2023 |volume=30 |issue=2 |doi=10.2139/ssrn.4419750|s2cid=258386262 }}</ref>

In July 2018, [[Sally Hines]], a [[University of Leeds]] professor of sociology and gender studies scholar, wrote in ''[[The Economist]]'' that feminism and trans rights have been falsely portrayed as being in conflict by a minority of anti-transgender feminists, who often "reinforce the extremely offensive trope of the trans woman as a man in [[Drag (clothing)|drag]] who is a danger to women". Hines criticized these feminists for fueling "rhetoric of paranoia and hyperbole" against trans people, saying that they abandon or undermine feminist principles in their anti-trans narratives, such as [[bodily autonomy]] and self-determination of gender, and employ "reductive models of biology and restrictive understandings of the distinction between sex and gender" in defense of such narratives. She concluded with a call for explicit recognition of anti-transgender feminism as a violation of equality and dignity, and "a doctrine that runs counter to the ability to fulfill a liveable life or, often, a life at all".<ref name="Hines 2018">{{cite news |date=13 July 2018 |title=Trans and Feminist Rights Have Been Falsely Cast in Opposition |newspaper=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/open-future/2018/07/13/trans-and-feminist-rights-have-been-falsely-cast-in-opposition |url-status=live |access-date=2 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502004748/https://www.economist.com/open-future/2018/07/13/trans-and-feminist-rights-have-been-falsely-cast-in-opposition |archive-date=2 May 2019 |author-first1=Sally |author-last1=Hines}}</ref>

Briar Dickey notes that "British 'trans-exclusionary radical feminist' (TERF) discourse has often been contextualised in fringe radical feminist thought", and argues that "the contextualisation of contemporary TERF discourse as an extension and evolution of fringe second-wave feminism [...] neglects its relationship to a wider international wave of anti-transgender sentiment" anchored in conservative and religious movements.<ref name=BD>{{cite journal |last1=Dickey |first1=Briar |title=Transphobic Truth Markets: Comparing Trans-hostile Discourses in British Trans-exclusionary Radical Feminist and US Right-wing Movements |journal=Journal of Diversity and Gender Studies |date=2023 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=34–47 |doi=10.21825/digest.85311|doi-access=free }}</ref>

Researcher Aleardo Zanghellini argues that "gender-critical feminism advocates reserving women's spaces for [[Cisgender|cis]] women" as well as that "Many problems in gender-critical thought are consistent with the explanation that paranoid structuralism is too often presupposed in gender-critical work".<ref name="Zanghellini 14"/>

[[Mauro Cabral Grinspan]], Ilana Eloit, [[David Paternotte]] and [[Mieke Verloo]] dislike the expression "gender-critical feminism", saying that it allows trans-exclusionary feminists to rebrand transphobic activism.<ref name=Grinspan/>

Abbie E. Goldberg argues that "trans-exclusionary radical feminism (TERF) has contained similar [[Cisnormativity|cisnormative]] arguments to those of social conservatives, promoting vilification of people with a trans lived experience in the guise of so-called gender-critical feminism" and that "this TERF approach has been used to promote exclusionary and discriminatory legislation, such as prohibiting equal access to public toilets and the right to be treated in accordance with one's gender in workplaces, accommodations, and public venues".<ref name="Goldberg">{{cite book |last1=Goldberg |first1=Abbie E. |title=The Sage Encyclopedia of LGBTQ+ Studies |date=2024 |publisher=[[SAGE Publications]] |isbn=9781071891384 |edition=2}}</ref>{{page needed|date=June 2024}}

=== Relationship with the anti-gender movement ===
{{further|Anti-gender movement}}
Bassi and LaFleur write that "the trans-exclusionary feminist (TERF) movement and the so-called anti-gender movement are only rarely distinguished as movements with distinct constitutions and aims".<ref name=Bassi/> Pearce et al. note that the concept of "[[gender ideology]]" "saw increasing circulation in [[TERF|trans-exclusionary radical feminist]] discourse" from around 2016.<ref name=Pearce/> Claire House noted in 2023 that "key streams within trans exclusionary women's and feminist movements increasingly engage in collaborative action with right-wing populist-centered anti-gender coalitions, which include right-wing religious, conservative, and right-wing extremist actors".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=House |first1=Claire |title='I'm Real, Not You': Roles and Discourses of Trans Exclusionary Women's and Feminist Movements in Anti-gender and Right-wing Populist Politics |journal=Journal of Diversity and Gender Studies |date=2023 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=14–32 |doi=10.21825/digest.85755 |url=https://www.digest.ugent.be/article/id/85755/ |doi-access=free |access-date=1 February 2024 |archive-date=1 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240201011620/https://www.digest.ugent.be/article/id/85755/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Claire Thurlow writes that "despite efforts to obscure the point, gender critical feminism continues to rely on transphobic tropes, moral panics and essentialist understandings of men and women. These factors also continue to link trans-exclusionary feminism to anti-feminist reactionary politics and other 'anti-gender' movements".<ref name=Thurlow>{{cite journal |last1=Thurlow |first1=Claire |title=From TERF to gender critical: A telling genealogy? |journal=[[Sexualities (journal)|Sexualities]] |date=2022 |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=962–978 |doi=10.1177/13634607221107827|s2cid=252662057 }}</ref>

[[UN Women]] has described the gender-critical, anti-gender and [[men's rights movement]]s as [[anti-rights movements]] that overlap in opposition to what they describe as "gender ideology", which the agency described as "a term used to oppose the concept of gender, women's rights, and the rights of LGBTIQ+ people broadly." They argued these groups have attempted to "frame equality for women and LGBTIQ+ people as a threat to so-called 'traditional' family values" and linked them to "hateful propaganda and disinformation to target and attempt to delegitimize people with diverse sexual orientations, gender identities, gender expressions, and sex characteristics."<ref name=unwomen>{{cite web |title=LGBTIQ+ communities and the anti-rights pushback: 5 things to know |date=28 May 2024 |url=https://www.unwomen.org/en/news-stories/explainer/2024/05/lgbtiq-communities-and-the-anti-rights-pushback-5-things-to-know |publisher=[[UN Women]] |access-date=15 June 2024 |archive-date=28 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240628133729/https://www.unwomen.org/en/news-stories/explainer/2024/05/lgbtiq-communities-and-the-anti-rights-pushback-5-things-to-know |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=thetimesantirights>{{cite news |title=UN Women says gender-critical activists are 'anti-rights movement' |url=https://www.thetimes.com/uk/society/article/un-women-says-gender-critical-activists-are-anti-rights-movement-b5mk7h9qr |access-date=16 June 2024 |work=The Times |archive-date=16 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240616192500/https://www.thetimes.com/uk/society/article/un-women-says-gender-critical-activists-are-anti-rights-movement-b5mk7h9qr |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Political alliances with conservatives and the far right ===
{{See also|Anti-gender movement}}

Some trans-exclusionary radical feminists have allied with conservative or far-right groups and politicians who oppose legislation that would expand transgender rights in the United States.<ref name="nbcnews_2019-01-29">{{cite news |last=Fitzsimons |first=Tim |date=29 January 2019 |title=Conservative group hosts anti-transgender panel of feminists 'from the left' |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/conservative-group-hosts-anti-transgender-panel-feminists-left-n964246 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503015702/https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/conservative-group-hosts-anti-transgender-panel-feminists-left-n964246 |archive-date=3 May 2019 |access-date=6 May 2019 |work=NBC News |language=en}}</ref><ref name="buzzfeed_2019-04-02">{{Cite web |last=Holden |first=Dominic |date=2 April 2019 |title=Republicans Are Trying To Kill An LGBT Bill In Congress By Arguing It Hurts Women |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/dominicholden/republicans-equality-act-lgbt-womens-rights |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505130133/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/dominicholden/republicans-equality-act-lgbt-womens-rights |archive-date=5 May 2019 |access-date=6 May 2019 |work=BuzzFeed News |language=en}}</ref> According to [[der Freitag]]: "TERF positions are now mostly heard from conservatives and right-wing extremists."<ref name="Studnik" />

Feminist philosopher [[Judith Butler]] has described the anti-gender movements as [[fascism|fascist]] trends and cautioned self-declared feminists from allying with such movements in targeting trans, [[Non-binary gender|non-binary]], and genderqueer people.<ref name="Butler idea of 'gender' backlash" /> Butler said that "it is painful to see that Trump's position that gender should be defined by biological sex, and that the evangelical and right-wing Catholic effort to purge 'gender' from education and public policy accords with the trans-exclusionary radical feminists' return to biological essentialism".<ref>{{cite news |title=Judith Butler artfully dismantles trans-exclusionary feminism and JK Rowling. Hang this in the Louvre immediately |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/09/23/judith-butler-trans-exclusionary-gender-critical-feminism-jk-rowling-transphobia/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211124054700/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/09/23/judith-butler-trans-exclusionary-gender-critical-feminism-jk-rowling-transphobia/ |archive-date=24 November 2021 |access-date=24 November 2021 |work=Pink News}}</ref> Sophia Siddiqui, the deputy editor of ''[[Race & Class]]'', has argued that "'gender critical' feminists play into the hands of far-right street forces and extreme-right electoral parties which would like to abolish anti-discrimination protections altogether" and that it "could have a damaging effect on global feminist and LGBT movements by reinforcing conservative ideas about gender and sexuality".<ref>{{cite web |title=Feminism, biological fundamentalism and the attack on trans rights |url=https://irr.org.uk/article/feminism-biological-fundamentalism-attack-on-trans-rights/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207211415/https://irr.org.uk/article/feminism-biological-fundamentalism-attack-on-trans-rights/ |archive-date=7 December 2021 |access-date=7 December 2021}}</ref> The [[Canadian Anti-Hate Network]] said that despite labelling themselves as feminists, TERF groups often collaborate with conservative and far-right groups.<ref name="CTV hate rise Canada" /> Serena Bassi and Greta LaFleur note that "gender-critical movements often reemploy the well-known right-wing populist opposition between 'the corrupt global elites' and 'the people'", noting the similarity of gender-critical beliefs to "far-right conspiracy theorizing".<ref name="Bassi" />

Gender studies scholar C. Libby has pointed to "burgeoning connections between trans-exclusionary radical feminism, "gender critical" writing, and transphobic evangelical Christian rhetoric".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Libby |first1=C |date=2022 |title=Sympathy, Fear, Hate: Trans-Exclusionary Radical Feminism and Evangelical Christianity |journal=[[Transgender Studies Quarterly]] |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=425–442 |doi=10.1215/23289252-9836078 |s2cid=253054962}}</ref>

In January 2019, [[The Heritage Foundation]], an American conservative think tank, hosted a panel of self-described radical feminists opposed to the US [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]].<ref name="nbcnews_2019-01-29" /> Heron Greenesmith of [[Political Research Associates]], an American liberal think tank, has said that the latest iteration of collaboration between conservatives and anti-transgender feminists is in part a reaction to the trans community's "incredible gains" in civil rights and visibility, and that anti-trans feminists and conservatives capitalize on a "scarcity mindset rhetoric" whereby civil rights are portrayed as a limited commodity and must be prioritized to cisgender women over other groups. Greenesmith compared this rhetoric to the right-wing tactic of prioritizing the rights of citizens over non-citizens and white people over people of colour.<ref name="nbcnews_2019-01-29" /> Bev Jackson, one of the founders of the [[LGB Alliance]], has argued in contrast that "working with The Heritage Foundation is sometimes the only possible course of action" since "the leftwing silence on gender in the US is even worse than in the UK".<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 August 2020 |title=LGB Alliance founder defends "feminists" working with Heritage Foundation |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/08/21/lgb-alliance-founder-bev-jackson-heritage-foundation-tweets/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210603012155/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/08/21/lgb-alliance-founder-bev-jackson-heritage-foundation-tweets/ |archive-date=3 June 2021 |access-date=7 December 2021}}</ref>

In a 2020 article in ''[[Lambda Nordica]]'', [[Erika Alm]] of the [[University of Gothenburg]] and [[Elisabeth L. Engebretsen]] of the [[University of Stavanger]], said that there was "growing convergence, and sometimes conscious alliances, between "gender-critical" feminists (sometimes known as TERFs – Trans-Exclusionary Radical Feminists), religious and social conservatives, as well as right-wing politics and even neo-Nazi and fascist movements" and that the convergence was linked to "their reliance on an essentialised and binary understanding of sex and/or gender, often termed 'bio-essentialism'".<ref name="Alm & Engebretsen 2020" /> Engebretsen has described the movement as a "complex threat to democracy".<ref name="Engebretsen">{{cite book |last1=Engebretsen |first1=Elisabeth L. |title=Populism and Science in Europe |date=2022 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-3-030-97534-0 |editor-last=Eslen-Ziya |editor-first=H. |editor-link=Hande Eslen-Ziya |pages=185–206 |chapter=Scientizing Gender? An Examination of Anti-Gender Campaigns on Social Media, Norway |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-97535-7_9 |access-date=28 June 2023 |editor2-last=Giorgi |editor2-first=A. |chapter-url=https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-97535-7_9 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220627074207/https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-97535-7_9 |archive-date=27 June 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> Another 2020 article, in ''[[The Sociological Review]]'', said that "the language of 'gender ideology' originates in anti-feminist and anti-trans discourses among right-wing Christians, with the Catholic Church acting as a major nucleating agent", and said that the term "saw increasing circulation in trans-exclusionary radical feminist discourse" from around 2016. It further said that "a growing number of anti-trans campaigners associated with radical feminist movements have openly aligned themselves with anti-feminist organisations".<ref name="Pearce" />

In a 2021 paper in ''[[Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society]]'', Hil Malatino of [[Pennsylvania State University]] said that "'gender-critical' feminism" in the US has "begun to build coalition with the evangelical Right around the legal codification of sex as a biological binary" and that "popular news media frames transphobia as part of a rational, enlightened, pragmatic response to what is variously called the 'trans lobby' and the 'cult of trans'".<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Malatino |first1=Hil |year=2021 |title=The Promise of Repair: Trans Rage and the Limits of Feminist Coalition |url=https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/713292?journalCode=signs |url-status=live |journal=Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society |volume=46 |issue=4 |pages=827–851 |doi=10.1086/713292 |s2cid=235304979 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211030181558/https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/713292?journalCode=signs |archive-date=30 October 2021 |access-date=7 December 2021}}</ref> Another 2021 paper, in ''[[Law and Social Inquiry]]'', said that "a coalition of Christian conservative legal organizations, conservative foundations, Trump administration officials, Republican party lawmakers, and trans-exclusionary radical feminists has assembled to redefine the right to privacy in service of anti-transgender politics" and that "social conservatives have cast the issue as one of balancing two competing rights claims rather than one of outright animus against a gender minority population".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wuest |first1=Joanna |year=2021 |title=A Conservative Right to Privacy: Legal, Ideological, and Coalitional Transformations in US Social Conservatism |journal=Law & Social Inquiry |volume=46 |issue=4 |pages=964–992 |doi=10.1017/lsi.2021.1 |s2cid=234808832 |doi-access=free}}</ref>

=== Misinformation and disinformation ===
T.J. Billiard in article on "TERF strategies" has stated that "[[misinformation]]—or, more specifically, [[disinformation]]—about trans topics has become the defining feature of public discourse on transgender rights".<ref name=":1" /> Cilia Williams et al. noted in an article on gender critical feminist discourse in Spain that "anti-trans  narratives  online [...] use  attacks,  misinformation,  and  self-defence  as  a  communication  strategy,  rather  than  debate  or  dialogue".<ref name=":2" /> Alyosxa Tudor has written that "strategic disinformation as [an] accelerator" has been used to push forward "hateful and anti-democratic agendas".<ref name=":3" />

== Controversies ==

=== Academic freedom ===
Conflict between gender-critical feminists and other feminists and transgender rights activists has resulted in controversies in which the principles of academic freedom have been invoked. Conflicts have erupted at university campuses.{{citation needed|date=June 2023}}

Kathleen Lowrey, who had allegedly been fired from her additional position as associate chair of undergraduate programs for the department of anthropology at the [[University of Alberta]] after displaying gender-critical posters on her office door, teaching gender-critical material in class, and showing up halfway through a student-run queer anthology event to start arguments about "the existence and validity of trans people with a trans man in the room",<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thegatewayonline.ca/2020/06/professor-lowrey-dismayed-over-dismissal-from-admin-role/ | title=Professor Lowrey dismayed over dismissal from admin role; others feel it is a positive step | date=11 June 2020 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208170803/https://thegatewayonline.ca/2020/06/professor-lowrey-dismayed-over-dismissal-from-admin-role/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/u-of-a-professor-says-she-was-dismissed-over-views-that-biological-sex-trumps-transgender-identity-for-policy-decisions/ | title=U of a professor says she was dismissed over views that biological sex trumps transgender identity for policy decisions | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208170801/https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/u-of-a-professor-says-she-was-dismissed-over-views-that-biological-sex-trumps-transgender-identity-for-policy-decisions/ | url-status=live }}</ref> published a paper in ''[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]]'' saying that she found it particularly distressing that "almost all of my most enthusiastic public attackers were feminist academic women" and that gender-critical feminists "root their analysis in the materiality of biological sex and take the oppression of women to be linked to the control of reproduction. In the present scholarly ecumene, this aligns them in some respects with scholars who are traditional and conservative, and explains why they, like conservatives, are so often in trouble with their institutions under present conditions".<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1007/s10508-021-01950-9 | title=Trans Ideology and the New Ptolemaism in the Academy | year=2021 | last1=Lowrey | first1=Kathleen | journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior | volume=50 | issue=3 | pages=757–760 | pmid=33660161 | s2cid=232112514 | doi-access=free }}</ref>

Carolyn Sale of the Center for Free Expression at Ryerson University condemned the university's decision, saying that "the idea that in a hush behind closed doors students can bring complaints that don't have to be proven true and can do so in order to protect their "safety" should alarm us all".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cfe.ryerson.ca/blog/2020/06/academic-freedom-and-perceptions-harm | title=Academic Freedom and Perceptions of Harm &#124; Centre for Free Expression | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208170812/https://cfe.ryerson.ca/blog/2020/06/academic-freedom-and-perceptions-harm | url-status=live }}</ref>

In September 2022, Laura Favaro published an article in ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' discussing her research into the climate of the debate among academics. Noting that she had interviewed 50 feminist academics in gender studies with a range of views on the subject, Favaro stated "my discussions left me in no doubt that a culture of discrimination, silencing and fear has taken hold across universities in England, and many countries beyond".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Favaro |first=Laura |date=15 September 2022 |title=Researchers are wounded in academia's gender wars |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/depth/researchers-are-wounded-academias-gender-wars |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220916233729/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/depth/researchers-are-wounded-academias-gender-wars |archive-date=16 September 2022 |access-date=4 October 2023 |website=Times Higher Education (THE) |language=en}}</ref> Favaro later began discrimination proceedings against [[City, University of London]], stating she had been "ostracised at her workplace and denied access to her research data" after the publication of her article.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Somerville |first=Ewan |date=15 April 2023 |title=University 'blocks' academic from her own gender wars research over 'dangerous' data |language=en-GB |work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/04/15/university-blocks-academic-gender-wars-research/ |access-date=4 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230508091117/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/04/15/university-blocks-academic-gender-wars-research/ |archive-date=8 May 2023 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=":8">{{Cite web |date=30 August 2023 |title=Laura Favaro: gender studies 'groupthink is forcing scholars out' |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/laura-favaro-gender-studies-groupthink-forcing-scholars-out |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230830174319/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/laura-favaro-gender-studies-groupthink-forcing-scholars-out |archive-date=30 August 2023 |access-date=4 October 2023 |website=Times Higher Education (THE) |language=en}}</ref>

City, University of London responded with a statement that it had a "legal obligation to protect freedom of expression that we take very seriously". It also took its "obligations with respect to ethics and integrity very seriously" and made clear that "any personal data processed in the course of any research [should be] processed in compliance with data protection legislation".<ref name=":8" />

=== Conflicts with other feminist and pro-equality groups ===
In February 2020, 28 feminist and LGBT groups in France co-signed a declaration titled ''Toutes des femmes'' denouncing trans-exclusionary feminism, saying that "questions disguised as 'legitimate concerns' quickly give way to more violent attacks" and that "it is a confusionist and conspiratorial ideological movement using the cover of feminism to disrupt real feminist fights.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.liberation.fr/debats/2020/02/26/le-debat-sur-la-place-des-femmes-trans-n-a-pas-lieu-d-etre_1779708/ | title=Le débat sur la place des femmes trans n'a pas lieu d'être | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=17 May 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210517001126/https://www.liberation.fr/debats/2020/02/26/le-debat-sur-la-place-des-femmes-trans-n-a-pas-lieu-d-etre_1779708/ | url-status=live }}</ref> The declaration has since also been signed by over 100 additional feminist, LGBT, and progressive groups.<ref name="Toutes des femmes">{{cite web | url=https://toutesdesfemmes.fr/signataires/ | title=Les signataires - Toutes des Femmes | date=25 February 2020 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=8 December 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211208170603/https://toutesdesfemmes.fr/signataires/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2021, over 110 women's and human rights organisations in Canada signed a statement stating that they "vehemently reject the dangerous and bigoted rhetoric and ideology espoused by Trans Exclusionary Radical 'Feminists' (TERFs)", and saying that "trans people are a driving force in our feminist movements and make incredible contributions across all facets of our society".<ref name="Canada 110">{{Cite web|url=https://www.actioncanadashr.org/news/2021-05-04-our-feminism-trans-inclusive|title=Our Feminism is Trans Inclusive. &#124; Action Canada for Sexual Health and Rights|access-date=8 December 2021|archive-date=12 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210612151421/https://www.actioncanadashr.org/news/2021-05-04-our-feminism-trans-inclusive|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Judith Butler]] said in 2020 that trans-exclusionary radical feminism is "a fringe movement that is seeking to speak in the name of the mainstream, and that our responsibility is to refuse to let that happen".<ref>{{cite news |title=Judith Butler on the culture wars, JK Rowling and living in "anti-intellectual times" |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/uncategorized/2020/09/judith-butler-culture-wars-jk-rowling-and-living-anti-intellectual-times |access-date=17 November 2021 |work=New Statesman |archive-date=17 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220417111403/https://www.newstatesman.com/uncategorized/2020/09/judith-butler-culture-wars-jk-rowling-and-living-anti-intellectual-times |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2021, the [[Council of Europe]] Committee on Equality and Non-Discrimination published a report titled ''Combating rising hate against LGBTI people in Europe'', which condemned "the highly prejudicial anti-gender, gender-critical and anti-trans narratives which reduce the fight for the equality of LGBTI people to what these movements deliberately mischaracterise as '[[gender ideology]]' or '[[LGBT "ideology"|LGBTI ideology]]'" and which said there was "a direct link between heteronormativity and heterosexism, on the one hand, and the growing anti-gender and gender-critical movements".<ref name="Council of Europe 2021">{{citation |url=https://assembly.coe.int/LifeRay/EGA/Pdf/TextesProvisoires/2021/20210921-RisingHateLGBTI-EN.pdf |title=Combating rising hate against LGBTI people in Europe (Provisional version) |first=Fourat |last=Ben Chika |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] Committee on Equality and Non-Discrimination |date=21 September 2021 |access-date=8 December 2021 |archive-date=23 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210923211038/https://assembly.coe.int/LifeRay/EGA/Pdf/TextesProvisoires/2021/20210921-RisingHateLGBTI-EN.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The report formed the basis of Resolution 2417, adopted in January 2022.<ref name=Resolution2417/>

In late-January 2018, over 1000 Irish feminists, including several groups such as the [[University College Dublin]] Centre of Gender, Feminisms & Sexualities, signed an open letter condemning a planned meeting in Ireland on UK Gender Recognition Act reforms organised by a British group opposing the reforms.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gcn.ie/ireland-says-no-to-terfs/ | title=Ireland Says No to TERFs | date=24 January 2018 | access-date=8 December 2021 | archive-date=24 February 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220224001108/https://gcn.ie/ireland-says-no-to-terfs/ | url-status=live }}</ref> The letter stated that "[t]rans people and particularly trans women are an inextricable part of our feminist community" and accused the British group of colonialism.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.irishcentral.com/news/irish-feminists-warn-away-british-terfs|title = "Stay away from Ireland," British anti-trans feminists told|date = 23 January 2018|access-date = 8 December 2021|archive-date = 1 December 2021|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211201205946/https://www.irishcentral.com/news/irish-feminists-warn-away-british-terfs|url-status = live}}</ref>

Sociologist Kelsy Burke argued that "TERFs aren't aligned with most feminists" and wrote that "most American feminists are far from trans-exclusionary and have long been among the most supportive groups of LGBTQ equality".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burke |first1=Kelsy |title=Feminists have long supported trans rights |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/made-by-history/2023/07/27/trans-rights-feminism-conservative-women/ |access-date=18 March 2024 |newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref>

=== Social media ===
The controversial Reddit community [[Controversial Reddit communities#GenderCritical|r/GenderCritical]] gathered a reputation as an anti-trans space. In June 2020, it was banned abruptly for violating new rules against "promoting hate". Members set up a similar community called Ovarit.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |date=2023-04-28 |title=TERFs and The Donald: The Future of Reddit's Banned Groups - The Atlantic |website=[[The Atlantic]] |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/12/reddit-ovarit-the-donald/617320/ |access-date=2023-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230428050258/https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/12/reddit-ovarit-the-donald/617320/ |archive-date=28 April 2023 }}</ref>

